<HEADLINE> France Warns Against "Conflagration" If Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- France today warned against
grave consequences from a failure of mediation by Gabon and the
United Nations in the conflict of the Congo Republic, saying that
a failure of peace efforts could result in the "conflagration" of
the country.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummalhardt said that
"a failure of the on-going (peace) efforts" made by Gabonese
President Omar Bongo and U.N. envoy Mohamed Sahnoun, who were
backed by seven other African heads of state, will be "very
grave".
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the renewed efforts of the African countries
would convince the Congolese parties to renounce at last violence
and resolve by dialogue the last points in dispute," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Renewed heavy fighting broke out today in Brazzaville, capital
of Congo Republic, between troops loyal to Congolese President
Pascal Lissouba and the militiamen of former president, General
Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state of eight African states and the U.N. envoy
meeting in Libreville appealed on Monday to the conflicting sides
to agree to an "effective and definite" ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
They also said that a peace-keeping force should be deployed in
Brazzaville by the end of this month under the auspices of the
United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
