<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Irish People Seek Legal Aid on Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of people to seek
legal advice on divorce in Ireland has doubled since the
legislation on divorce was officially implemented in February,
according to press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 people are waiting for their first divorce
consultation with a Legal Aid Board solicitor, compared with 1,500
in February, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The clients at one center would now have to wait almost a year
to be seen and the situation across the country was getting worse.
</P>
<P>
Legal Aid Board chief Frank Goodman was reported as saying that
some 1,000 people sought legal advice on divorce before it was
officially legalized.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen 700 of these but a further 500 have since made
contact -- which means 1,000 people are now on the waiting list in
respect of divorce," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ireland, which was the only West European country where divorce
was still illegal, staged a national referendum on whether to
legalize divorce in November 1995 and eventually divorce was
legalized by only a half per cent margin.
</P>
<P>
In January, a dying man secured Ireland's first divorce of
modern times when he successfully appealed to the country's High
Court that his rights were being infringed by the delay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
