<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, Italy Pledges to Boost Economic Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev and Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi today expressed
a mutual desire to expand bilateral trade and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev said the two countries' two-way trade was up 30
percent to 300 million U.S. dollars in 1996; and surged 70 percent
in the first half of this year over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh leader noted, during a meeting here with the Italian
premier, that there were 18 Italian companies and 46
Kazakh-Italian ventures operating in this central Asian country.
</P>
<P>
There would be good prospect for Italy, the most successful
European country in boosting small and medium-sized businesses, to
work with Kazakhstan and help it achieve in the same area, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, here since Monday on a three-day visit, said his country
was willing to further its cooperation with Kazakhstan, a former
Soviet republic now entering a new political and economic stage.
</P>
<P>
Italy, he said, also hoped to expand direct trade links with
Kazakhstan, rather than going through Germany, Switzerland and
Turkey as much of the bilateral transactions currently do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
