<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Prices Up Moderately in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices
increased by a moderate 0.2 percent in August despite the fact
that gasoline prices soared by the biggest amount since the
Persian Gulf crisis in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Labor Department reported that the Consumer Price
Index (CPI) increase matched a similar 0.2 percent rise in July.
</P>
<P>
The report said that energy prices rose by 1.7 percent in
August, the biggest monthly advance since a 3 percent rise in
April 1996. Gasoline prices were up 5.4 percent, the biggest
one-month increase since a 7 percent spike in October 1990.
</P>
<P>
Food prices increased 0.4 percent in the month, compared with a
0.2 percent rise in July.
</P>
<P>
Through August, the core rate of inflation has been rising at
an annual rate of 2.2 percent, even better than 2.6 percent rise
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The good performance in the underlying inflation rate in August
reflected a 1 percent plunge in clothing costs, the biggest
one-month drop since August 1989.
</P>
<P>
New vehicle prices were also down in August, dropping 0.1
percent. Used car prices were down an even larger 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the first eight months of this year, U.S. inflation at the
consumer level has been rising at an annual rate of just 1.6
percent, less than half of the 3.3 percent increase turned in
during 1996.
</P>
<P>
This exceptional performance on inflation has been the primary
reason that the U.S. Federal Reserve has held off increasing
interest rates even though strong economic growth has pushed
unemployment below 5 percent for five straight months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
