<HEADLINE> WHO: Five Million Children's Lives Can Be Saved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 11 million children
under the age of five die annually but at least five million of them
can be saved, the World Health Organization (WHO) said in a press
release here today.
</P>
<P>
70 percent of the 11 million children, around eight million, die
from one or more of five causes: pneumonia, diarrhea, measles,
malaria and malnutrition, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
However, with the joint strategy of Integrated Management of
Childhood Illness (IMCI), health workers will be more capable in
detecting the onset of the five greatest killers of children under
five.
</P>
<P>
The successful worldwide implementation of IMCI could prevent
the deaths of at least five million children, WHO said in its
press release issued after the First Global Review and
Coordination Meeting on IMCI, held in Santo Domingo, Dominican
Republic, from September 9 to 12.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting also learned that doctors' current drug
usage costs could be reduced by almost 80 percent using IMCI. Families
taking their children for treatment were substantially more satisfied
with the care the children received when they were looked after by
IMCI-trained health workers.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies have been carried out in three districts in Uganda.
The three main goals of IMCI are to train health workers, improve the
ability of health systems to deliver quality care, and improve family
and community practices in relation to health care. IMCI advocates
that health workers adopt a holistic approach to examining and
treating children so that a child being treated for one illness is
also checked and treated for the other major childhood killers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
