<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lloyds Expects Impending Revolution in European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) - Aging populations in Europe
will cause large shifts in savings patterns in the first part of
the 21st century, Lloyds Bank expects.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Foley, Economic Adviser of the Lloyds Bank Group, told
a seminar here today that the direct effect of aging will be to
raise European saving rates by around 2 percent until around 2010,
and thereafter to reduce saving, compared with today's levels.
</P>
<P>
The direct effect will be swamped by the indirect impact on
saving resulting from growing crises in public pension systems, he
expected, saying that eventually governments will be forced to
reduce the generosity of pension payments, with profound effects
on private saving.
</P>
<P>
Foley estimated that average European private rates may rise
sharply in the next ten year - by perhaps 5 percent - in
anticipation of reduced public pensions.
</P>
<P>
In the longer term, he said, a switch from public to private
provision for retirement will result in much lower saving rates,
falling to zero in some countries, as the growing elderly
population draws down past savings.
</P>
<P>
The initial savings surge is likely to depress demand, causing
slow growth and high unemployment in many European countries.
Inflation is likely to fall even further from current levels, and
interest rates will be very low, Foley added.
</P>
<P>
However, Foley argued that the longer term collapse in
aggregate saving will strengthen demand relative to potential
output, especially given the decline in workforces.
</P>
<P>
European economies will need to borrow externally to finance
labor saving investment, and the period of low inflation may come
to an end, he conclude. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
