<HEADLINE> UK Women Still Lag Behind Men in Pay, Job Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- British women still lag far
behind men in earnings and job status, according to a report today
by the Equal Opportunities Commission.
</P>
<P>
The report, Facts About Women and Men 1997, said that although
women make up 51 percent of the country's population and 45
percent of the paid workforce, they make up only 33 percent of
managers and administrators, six percent of police sergeants and
15 percent of legal partners.
</P>
<P>
It noted that women comprise only 18 percent of members of
Parliament and 31 percent of public appointments, and only one in
10 of the judiciary is a woman.
</P>
<P>
In the field of pay, although the gap has narrowed, it has done
so by only seven percent in the past 20 years. Working full time,
women continue to earn only 80 percent of men's average hourly
wage.
</P>
<P>
The situation is not changed even in retirement. The average
personal income of women aged 65-plus is only 58 percent of the
average for men in the same age group.
</P>
<P>
The report added that 67 percent of the country's women and 77
percent of men of working age have jobs. However, 45 percent of
women employees work part-time, compared to eight percent of men.
</P>
<P>
The commision's chairman Kamlesh Bahl said that these figures
show that women are becoming more visible, but that there is no
cause for complacency about their progress towards equality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
