<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Third UK Lifters Unavailable for Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The coming weekend would be
the last chance for some one third of the lifters in British
Amateur Weightlifters Association who refused to take doping test,
an anti-doping official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Michele Verroken, director of the ethics and anti-doping
section of the UK Sports Council, told a news conference on
Tuesday she had held "deep discussions" with the BAWA about the
adequacy of their testing program.
</P>
<P>
Verroken said she would hold crisis talks with the BAWA this
weekend and expects the association to accept responsibility for
testing lifters.
</P>
<P>
Verroken was unveiling her section's 1996/7 annual report which
showed positive tests for anabolic steroids had risen to 27 from
15 in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
Five weightlifters received bans for positive tests last year
and Verroken highlighted the high percentage of weightlifters who
had made themselves unavailable for testing -- a rise to 31
percent from 23 last year.
</P>
<P>
There were no positive tests in Britain's Olympic or
paraOlympic teams for the Atlanta Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
