<HEADLINE> Indonesia Offers Apologies for Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
 apologized here today for woodland and forest fires in several
parts of the country, which have had a negative impact on
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"To the communities of neighboring countries which have been
disturbed by fires in our territory, Indonesia offers its most
sincere apologies," the president said when opening the Seventh
ASEAN Ministerial Meeting on the Environment.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia has actually done its utmost to prevent the
fires.
</P>
<P>
"However, the sheer vastness of our bushes and forests,
together with the prolonged drought, has created insurmountable
obstacles in the efforts to prevent and control the fires," he
told the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
At least 300,000 hectares of forest, mostly in Sumatra and
Kalimantan, have been destroyed by fire in Indonesia this year.
</P>
<P>
The haze caused by the fires has reached unhealthy levels here
and in Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of Environment Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said
earlier that about 20 million people are in danger of respiratory
problems due to the thick smoke.
</P>
<P>
On economic development as it concerns environmental
preservation efforts, Soeharto said environmental issues have been
incorrectly used by certain parties as a condition for
international trade.
</P>
<P>
In face of environmental, democracy and human rights questions,
the ASEAN should take concerted steps, which are reasonable, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
