<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Production Varies in Kenya's Different Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The estimated maize
production in Rift Valley and Nyanza provinces may decline while
food supply has increased significantly in other provinces during
the current long rain season.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today said that the maize production in Rift
Valley Province was estimated at 1.24 million tons in the long
rains, compared with 1.35 million tons in 1996 and 1.5 million
tons in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Irregular rainfall has hit the north Rift Valley where maize
and wheat crop might lose up to 50 percent production if more
rains are not received in the next two weeks, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
A senior agricultural official was quoted as saying "if the
dry weather continues to the end of this month, we might have a
crop failure of up to 40 percent in the whole of north Rift
region."
</P>
<P>
Market analysts predicted that due to the fall of food
production, the price of maize, the staple food for the Kenyans,
is expected to increase to 2,000 Kenyan Shillings a bag,
compared to last year's 1,200 Shillings and
600 Shillings in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that delayed long rains, mid-season flooding
and a prolonged dry spell after May had resulted in a significant
reduction in output in Nyanza province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, food supply has increased significantly at the
markets in the early harvesting areas of Eastern, Coast and
Western provinces where maize price has declined by between 10 to
25 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the key maize producing districts like Uasin Gishu, Trans
Nzoia, Nandi, Kericho and Bungoma, harvesting is not expected
until November and December.
</P>
<P>
The six districts are expected to produce up to 40 percent of
the long rains national output of the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Kenya had suffered a serious drought during last two rain
seasons and the government has imported 375,000 tons of maize in
the past two months in order to meet the shortage of food supply
caused by the drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
