<HEADLINE> Central Asian States, NATO Begin Military Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Troops from three Central
Asian countries, the United States, Turkey and Russia have started
a military exercise codenamed "97-Central Asian Peace-keeping
Battalion".
</P>
<P>
The war game, starting on Monday, involved 1,400 soldiers from
Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, the United States, Turkey and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
As a highlight of the drill, said a Kazakhstan Telegraph Agency
report today, 500 soldiers of the U.S. 82th Airborne Division and
40 Central Asian peace-keepers took a 17-hour non-stop flight.
</P>
<P>
The "unprecedented" long-distance airlift operation began in
the U.S. state of North Carolina and ended up in Chimkent, where
the Kazakh Air Force was providing air cover for the troops'
arrival.
</P>
<P>
As the first stage of the exercise, said the report, the
airborne troops joined allied ground forces there to launch an
attack on imaginary enemies who had occupied a local airport.
</P>
<P>
The second stage of the military exercise is scheduled to take
place in Uzbekistan, and the whole exercise is expected to end on
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
