<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Members Urged to Cooperate in Handling Haze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today hoped that the
ASEAN spirit would serve as a basis for cooperation in tackling
the thick haze which has been enveloping some countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Seventh ASEAN Meeting on the Environment here,
Malaysian Minister of Science, Technology and Environment Law
Hieng Ding noted that the haze, which has hit Malaysia and
Singapore, was caused by thousands of forest and bush fires raging
across Sumatra and Kalimantan, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The result has been an air pollution surpassing healthy ranges,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the air pollution resulting from the thick haze
has reached Malaysia and is registering a reading of 390 on the
air pollution indicator (API).
</P>
<P>
Under the Malaysian API, readings from zero to 50 indicate good
air quality, 51 to 100 moderate, 101 to 200 unhealthy, 201 to 300
very unhealthy and 300 to 500 hazardous.
</P>
<P>
"What's most important now is how such problem, which tends to
occur every year, can be settled as soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, he said, the Malaysian government
will suggest that the Indonesian government find the best solution
to the problem, including the establishment of a special force
group by all ASEAN countries and giving it the task of putting out
the fires.
</P>
<P>
He also said Malaysia wants a memorandum of understanding on the
problem with Indonesia and hopes Singapore and Brunei will support
the measure.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, opened by Indonesian President Soeharto today, is
attended by representatives from the nine member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) -- Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines, Laos,
Myanmar and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
