<HEADLINE> Diana's Bodyguard Capable of Communication: Doctor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Trevor Rees-Jones, the
bodyguard of the late Princess of Wales Diana and her friend Dodi
al Fayed, is "perfectly conscious" and can communicate, said
doctors of the French emergency medical rescue group Public
Assistance today.
</P>
<P>
But investigators in charge of the Diana case are still not
expecting to have his testimony in the coming weeks, because
Rees-Jones is extremely week from his injury.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones, who is being treated in the heavily-guarded
Pitie-Salpetriere Hospital in Paris, is the only survivor of the
crash of the Mercedes S-280 sedan in which Diana, Dodi, Rees-Jones
and the car's driver Henri Paul was traveling in the mid-night
between August 30 and 31 in downtown Paris.
</P>
<P>
"The state of Mr. Trevor Rees-Jones has noticeably improved. He
could be separated from the artificial ventilation and the
infection of his pulmonary contusion has been put under control,"
said Public Assistance in a communique.
</P>
<P>
It said that Rees-Jones, who is suffering from moderate brain
contusion, severe facial traumatism and pulmonary contusion, can
communicate well although he gets tired easily.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports said that he could not speak and only
communicate by blinking, and doctors had earlier warned that he
could suffer from amnesia.
</P>
<P>
Doctors conducted a 10-hour operation on his face on September
4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
