<HEADLINE> Proposal to Reshuffle Cambodia's Cabinet Fails at Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A proposal to partly
reshuffle the cabinet of Cambodia failed to go through the
country's National Assembly, or congress, today.
</P>
<P>
The 67 votes for the proposal, presented by the cabinet last
Tuesday, are not enough for its passage, which requires votes by
two-thirds of the 120 assembly members, of whom 97 voted today.
</P>
<P>
After the vote, Second Prime Minister Hun Sen told the press
that the result of the ballot demonstrated democratic spirit, with
which every congressman has the right to support or oppose.
</P>
<P>
But Hun Sen said the assembly will vote again on the proposal
after he and First Prime Minister Ung Huot return from the 52nd
U.N. General Assembly opening later this month in New York.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, the number of deputy prime ministers will
be increased from two to five and ministers of state from four to
10. Some ministers and secretaries of state will be replaced.
</P>
<P>
Local media believed that the failure of the proposal to be
approved by the National Assembly reflected disputes within the
royalist FUNCINPEC party, led by ousted Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Some of the proposed new cabinet members belong to a separatist
faction of the FUNCINPEC party while most of the FUNCINPEC members
of the National Assembly are from the mainstream faction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
