<HEADLINE> Lesotho Parliament Opens For Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Media reporters in
Lesotho today resume coverage of parliament proceedings, after a
ban of nearly three weeks due to political tension.
</P>
<P>
Radio Lesotho, however, said members of the public will
continue to be prevented from attending sessions of the National
Assembly until further notice.
</P>
<P>
Reporters and the public were barred from parliament toward
the end of last month by the Speaker, Teboho Kolane, following
tension among legislators.
</P>
<P>
The situation was caused by an announcement by Prime Minister
Ntsu Mokhehle, calling members of the Basotoland Congress Party
(BCP) as the opposition in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle broke away from the party in June to form the Lesotho
Congress For Democracy and declared it the governing political
body.
</P>
<P>
But the BCP law makers insist they are not the opposition in
parliament because they were duly elected under their party
ticket.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the expulsion of the journalists and the public
from the National Assembly is the first such incident in the
history of the Lesotho parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
