<HEADLINE> Norway's Labor Government Voted Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSLO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Early returns of Norwegian
general elections published today suggested that the Labor
government was voted out by the Nordic nation's citizens.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government will resign as its support rate dropped to
35.1 percent from 36.9 percent in 1993 elections, which was set by
Prime Minister Thorbjoern Jagland as the minimum for his stay.
</P>
<P>
The resignation is expected to be tendered after the leftist
government presented the draft budget for the next financial year
to the congress on October 13.
</P>
<P>
The far-right Progress Party, which obtained 15.3 percent of
the votes, a nine percentage points jump from 1993 elections,
replaced the Conservative Party, whose support rate fell to 14.3
percent from 16.9 percent, as the second biggest party of Norway.
</P>
<P>
The three parties of the central bloc won 26.1 percent of the
votes, 96.9 percent of which has been counted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
