<HEADLINE> Full Moon Eclipse Visible From Southern African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- This century's last
full eclipse of the moon visible from southern African skies
will take place tonight.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers here said today that the moon will take on a
reddish hue during the eclipse--a phenomenon in which earth oasses
in front of the sun and its shadow falls across the moon.
</P>
<P>
Residents in South Africa, Lesotho, Swaziland, Namibia and
Botswana can view the eclipse that appears as a dark shadow moving
over the moon and then totally covering it.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse will start at five GMT or seven o'clok this
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
