<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Government Approves Plan to Hike Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government
approved a package of tax plans on Monday to raise the value-added
tax (VAT) from 12 percent to 22 percent beginning from October 1.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers also decided to increase business tax
on cigarettes, imported No. 89 gasoline and lubricant to 70
percent, 60 percent and 80 percent respectively, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Though increase of business taxes on other items will be
smaller, it is widely believed here that the rise of VAT and
business tax will result in an overall hike of price index.
</P>
<P>
The package is pending the approval of Albanian parliament
scheduled for session today. It is reported that the Socialist
Party, which constitutes a majority in parliament, has different
opinions about the package and many Socialist congressmen have
expressed their opposition.
</P>
<P>
The VAT hike, aiming at cutting the huge budget deficit, was
proposed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) as one of the
main conditions for providing economic aid to the country.
</P>
<P>
Albania's budget deficit reached 30 billion lek (1 U.S. dollar
equals to 143 lek) at the beginning of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano is scheduled to present the
tax package, if it get through in the parliament, to the IMF and
World Bank annual meeting in Hong Kong on September 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
