<HEADLINE> Nigeria Cancels Results of 35 Percent of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The results of 117,680
candidates for this year's university matriculation examination
have been canceled in Nigeria for various alleged offenses such
as examination malpractices, absenteeism to improper filling of
forms.
</P>
<P>
According to the Joint Admissions and Matribulation Board
(JAMB) today, the figure represented 35 percent of the 376,000
candidates who completed and returned the application forms for
the examination in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 21.56 percent candidates were found guilty of
malpractices during the examination.
</P>
<P>
JAMB Registrar Bello Salim who decried the massive cheating
appealed to the public to intensify the campaign against
examination malpractices so that the menace could be completely
eliminated from the educational system. 
