<HEADLINE> Ulster Unionists Said Not to Attend Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) - A bomb exploded near a police
station at Markethill near the Northern Irish town of Portadown
this noon, causing substantial damage, according to reports from
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened on the second day of a new round of
multi-party peace talks on the future of Northern Ireland, in
which Sinn Fein, political wing of IRA guerrillas was admitted for
the time.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened after an uncoded warning was telephoned
to BBC Belfast office about a van parked near the police station.
</P>
<P>
"At two minutes to 12 this vehicle explodeed. There was
substantial damage to the police station and surrounding area. We
have no reports of casualties," a police source said.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionists have planned to attend the multi-party
talks "as soon as possible", but said they would not sit under the
same roof with Sinn Fein until the bombers were identified.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's two main guerrilla groups, the Irish
Republican Army and Loyalist organizations fighting to keep the
province British, are both claimed observing ceasefires.
</P>
<P>
However, Chief Constable Ronnie Flanayan in Belfast stressed
that not all terrorist groups were observing truce. He said the
police had remained vigilant and had done "everything
appropriate". 
</P>
</TEXT>
