<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demirel: Turkey Wants Good Ties with All Arabs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Trying to allay Arab worries
over Turkey's growing ties with Israel, President Suleyman Demirel
today said Ankara is keen to deepen ties with all Arab countries
"for the good of the region."
</P>
<P>
"Turkey sees that the prospects of peace are great and should
be invested," Demirel said after talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a lot of misunderstanding in respect of the
relations between Turkey and Israel. Turkey is to join the
U.S. and Israel in a three-way naval exercise in eastern
Mediterranean in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers under a military cooperation accord
concluded between Turkey and Israel in February 1996 provoked
outcries from Arab countries, especially Syria which regards
itself as the imaginary enemy of the war games.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish-Israeli relations are not directed against any
country," Demirel said, adding the Turkey-Israel joint defense
agreement is just one of similar agreements Ankara signed with 28
countries.
</P>
<P>
Demirel reaffirmed the military agreement has no other purpose
than training on search and rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
"It is illogical to think of probable future military
operations between Turkey and Israel because, as I have explained
before, Turkey has no problems whatsoever with the Arab world," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mubarak said Egypt does not object to Turkey's
relations with Israel so long as their relations and agreements,
as Demirel has asserted, are not targeted against anyone.
</P>
<P>
"At first we were worried by the Turkish-Israeli military
maneuvers but now I accept President Demirel's assertions that
their exercises are only for search and rescue purposes," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara-Cairo relations are very good, Mubarak said, "We
want relations to continue in the same way and even better."
</P>
<P>
Demirel arrived in Alexandria this morning for a one-day visit
to Egypt aimed at enhancing relations with the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The Egypt-Turkey summit, which was previously set for May, was
postponed after Turkey announced its decision to hold joint
military maneuvers with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
