<HEADLINE> Greece Hails Development in Cyprus as "Positive" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece today welcomed the
latest development of situation in Cyprus, saying that the
agreement reached by Cyprus' two communities to meet again was "a
positive development."
</P>
<P>
"The agreement reached on Cyprus following U.S. mediation for
direct talks between President Clerides and mr. Denktash on
security matters is a positive development," said Greek Foreign
Undersecretary Yannos Kranidiotis today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright reportedly announced
today that Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash would meet soon to discuss security issues
regarding the divided island republic.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis emphasized that the demilitarization of Cyprus was
a fundamental aim of Athens, and hoped that the discussions on
disarmament would be "a first step in that direction."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas today
also said that president Clerides hoped to forge a rapprochement
on issue of security throughout the meeting and that a similar
expression of goodwill was hoped for from the Cypriot Turkish
side.
</P>
<P>
Athens hoped for the speediest demilitarization of the island,
he said, adding that Greece accepted anything that could improve
on the current situation. 
</P>
