<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Drafts Laws to Protect Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The work has started to draft
regulations which will control the use of imported chemicals
which deplete the ozone layer, Zimbabwe's Mines, Environment and
Tourism Minister Simon Moyo said here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the work is being done in conjunction with the Ministry of
Health and Child Welfare together with the Attorney General's
Office.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during the celebrations of the
International Ozone Layer Day which was set by the United Nations
General Assembly on December 19, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said, "Our industry, particularly the refrigeration
service industry, should take the necessary measures to stop
venting or emitting chlorofluorocarbons (CFCS) into the
atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
Those servicing refrigerators and air conditioning equipment
should use the recovery and reclamation equipment available in
the country to avoid emitting dangerous chemicals into the
atmosphere, Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has a program strategy of a 100 percent reduction of
all CFCS by year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The minister presented prizes to schools that participated in
the ozone layer protection competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
