<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evidence Show German, U.S. Planes Collide over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Evidence so far available
indicated that two German and United States military planes that
went missing late Saturday over the South Atlantic had collided in
mid-air, said German Defense Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
International search has found debris of the American C-141
Starlifter among the wreckage from the crashed German Tupolev 154,
according to the ministry. This confirmed the assumption that the
two missing aircraft collided in mid-air.
</P>
<P>
No further details were immediately available, said the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Searchers saw little hope of finding survivors of the air
collision. There were altogether 33 people aboard the German and
U.S. military planes, 24 of them aboard the German Tupolev,
including three women.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said earlier today that the body
of a woman had been recovered, the identity of whom was still to
be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
More debris were found today 30 kilometres north off the area
where the first pieces were discovered on Monday, which was 255
kilometres (142 nautical miles) northwest off Walvis Bay of
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said the location where the German aircraft went down has
now been clearly identified.
</P>
<P>
The German Air Force Tupolev 154 went missing late Saturday en
route from Cologne to Cape Town. The plane had sent no emergency
signal and the last radio signal from it was registered when it
was about 1,500 kilometres west off Angola. It did not land in
Windhoek at 18:30 Saturday as planned for a stopover.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military transport plane with nine people on board was
on its way from Windhoek to Ascension island when it disappeared
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.S. plane took off 90 minutes ahead
of schedule, but the German Tupolev was not informed of this for
reasons yet unclear.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
