<HEADLINE> Ireland Urged to Resist Anti-Refugee Prejudice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Ireland should grasp the
unique opportunity to guard against the kind of racism found
throughout the rest of Europe, according to Ireland's new
representative to the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the annual general meeting of the Irish Refugee
Council in Dublin, Ms Hope Hanlan was quoted by press reports
reaching here as saying that Ireland, which had not been
corrupted, "should have the opportunity to do the right thing
before racism rears its ugly head".
</P>
<P>
It is commonly regarded that Ireland had been an "oasis" in
Europe in its treatment of refugees, but it now stood "at a
crossroads".
</P>
<P>
The Dublin Council meeting repeated its call on the Irish
government to fully implement the Refugee Act, and to develop
support and integration services for refugees without delay.
</P>
<P>
John O'Neil, director of the Refugee Agency, said that he
regretted the lack of a strong voice in the Irish government
opposing racism and promoting a positive image of refugees and
multi-culturalism.
</P>
<P>
The Irish government is planning to appoint more than 70
retired gardai (policemen) and civil servants to process
applications for asylum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
