<HEADLINE> Sudanese Troops Set to Recover Occupied Territories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Al-Bashir announced today that the Sudanese Armed Forces are all
set to restore the territories occupied by the Eritrean troops in
east Sudan.
</P>
<P>
During his visit today to the Tokar governorate in the east
Sudan's Red Sea state, the president said the morale of the armed
forces was high, according to the Sudan news agency.
</P>
<P>
Tokar has been the scene of military operations mounted by the
Eritrea-backed Sudanese opposition forces. Eritrea severed its
ties with Sudan in December 1994, accusing Sudan of interfering in
its internal affairs and supporting the Eritrean "Islamic Jihad"
opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
The accusation was promptly denied by Sudan. However, the
Sudanese opposition forces have been using Eritrean territory as a
launching pad for cross-border attacks deep into Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir's eastward tour also covered Port Sudan, which he
visited Monday, and Senkat. He was accompanied by Defense Minister
Hassan Abdul-Rahman Ali and a number of senior Army officers.
</P>
<P>
The president is also scheduled to visit the Halayeb region, a
disputed area with Egypt. There has been mounting tension over the
past two weeks in the disputed Halayeb triangle, where the
Sudanese authorities accused Egypt of undertaking military
operations.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Tokar, Al-Bashir also announced to release
political prisoners in the Red Sea state as well as the opposition
elements which have taken up arms against the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
