<HEADLINE> Kenyan Ruling Party Resolves to Campaign for Moi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) resolved today to campaign for President
Daniel arap Moi's re-election and commit constitutional reforms
package drafted by both KANU and opposition lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
KANU is committed to the reforms and "ready for peaceful
elections which should be free and fair and may the best win,"
KANU Secretary-General Joseph Kamotho said after Moi formally
accepted his nomination as KANU's sole presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
The one-day KANU Special National Delegates Conference,
attended by around 5,000 people from all tribes in all the eight
provinces of the east African state, approved the nomination
unanimously with jubilant chanting this morning.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party general election is coming soon, Kamotho
added. Local analysts say the election is most likely to be held
in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 74 and in power for 19 years, is widely believed to win
his last campaign for the five-year-term presidency mainly due to
the opposition's split as well as strong support for him by
various small tribes and Asian Kenyans who weigh heavily on the
country's economic lifelines.
</P>
<P>
However, the party elections failed to be held at today's
conference, causing some delegates' complaints. Kamotho said
after the general election, another KANU national delegates
conference will be convened for the issue.
</P>
<P>
The last KANU national delegate conference was held in
December 1991 also for the same agenda on the eve of the
first-ever multi-party election in Kenya in the following year.
</P>
<P>
More than two-third parliamentary members, at least 40 of them
from the opposition, last week approved Inter-Parties
Parliamentary Group's package on a raft of constitutional and
social reforms.
</P>
<P>
The package recommended the repeal or revision of 12 laws
described as "oppressive", the expansion of Kenya's Electoral
Commission to bring in members nominated by the opposition, and
the equal access to state media for the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
