<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting Held on Improving African Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Communications ministers of
African countries met here today to study the projected African
submarine cable known as "Africa One."
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting was organized by the project's
coordination committee in cooperation with the International
Communications Union.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the ministers are to join specialists and
African and foreign investors to examine ways and means to
accomplish this project at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
The project was designed to improved communications between the
African continent and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's meeting, Ahmed Laouyan, chairman of the
project's coordination committee, said the "Africa One" represents
a completely integrated regional communications system comprising
a 39,000-kilometer-long cable of optical fibers linking all
African states with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the project was launched in late 1993 on
the initiative of the International Communications Union, with the
joint efforts of the African Satellite Communications
Organization and the African Communications Union.
</P>
<P>
He added that the "Africa One" project will link some 29 points
in coastal African states, while land-locked states will plug in
through ordinary or satellite lines. The total cost of the project
amounts to 1.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The coordination committee of the "Africa One" project
comprises representatives of the International Communications
Union, the African Satellite Communications Organization, the
African Communications Union, and delegates from Tunisia,
Cameroons, Kenya, Zimbabwe, Ivory Coast and South Africa. This
committee supervises the management of the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
