<HEADLINE> Gap between Rich and Poor Widening in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The gap between the rich and
poor is widening in Germany with the numbers of the social welfare
recipients and those of the top income bracket both increasing
sharply within the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
According to Ursula Engelen-Kefer, vice-chairperson of the
German Federation of Labour Unions, the number of people who are
dependent on social welfare benefits had grown by about 800,000 to
nearly 2.5 million in western Germany over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
In the eastern half of the country, the figures also had jumped
by 20 percent to about 300,000 since 1991.
</P>
<P>
In Germany as a whole, there were about 2.8 million social
welfare recipients in 1996, with the hardest-hit being the jobless
people, divorced women and families with many children.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of people with a monthly net income of
more than 10,000 German marks (about 5,600 U.S. dollars) had also
increased six times over the past decade, the union leader said.
</P>
<P>
The widening division between the rich and poor had aroused
many social problems and is becoming the catalyst for
right-extremist and xenophobic sentiments in Germany, she warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
