<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Confirms Shelton for Joint Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today
unanimously confirmed Army General Henry Shelton to be the next
chairman of the U.S. military Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
Shelton, who led U.S. forces in Haiti and now the head of the
U.S. Special Operations Command, replaces General John
Shalikashvili, who will retire at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old Shelton will be the third Army general in a row
to be the two-year term chairman that traditionally has rotated
among Army, Navy and Air Force officers.
</P>
<P>
At his nomination hearing before the Senate Armed Services
Committee earlier this month, Shelton said he supported President
Bill Clinton's plan to remove troops from Bosnia in mid-1998. He
also expressed hied support for efforts to modernize U.S. weaponry
for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Shelton's nomination in July came after Air Force General
Joseph Ralston, vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs, withdrew from
the running due to revelations he had an adulterous affair in the
past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
