<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medicare Computer Overhaul Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Government has
canceled a multimillion-dollar computer system overhaul meant to
simplify its Medicare program billing and help root out fraud.
</P>
<P>
Medicare is the federal health insurance program covering
millions of elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
"The cost and pace of work were unacceptable," Medicare
spokesman Chris Peacock said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Medicare's current computer setup -- 10 separate systems used
by 72 private insurance companies that process Medicare claims --
turned out to be more difficult to reorganize than expected.
</P>
<P>
Members of Congress criticized the project earlier this year
after discovering it was over budget and behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) ordered the
main private contractor, GTE, to end the job last month, after
rethinking the project during a summer-long suspension of most
work.
</P>
<P>
Department officials said they have decided to make incremental
improvements over time, some building on GTE's work.
</P>
<P>
GTE had assigned 90 employees to the Medicare project. The
company has been paid 43 million dollars to date, according to
Medicare. GTE's original contract was for 19 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
HHS officials had trumpeted the modernization as a way to speed
payments, improve customer service and cut out fraud in the
Medicare program, which overpaid health care providers by 23
billion dollars last year, according to a recent audit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Places Mineral Industry as Major Pillar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Geology
and Mines Marcos Samondo said today that the geological and
mineral industry will become a major pillar in the country's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement to the Angola News Agency in the central
city of Sumbe.
</P>
<P>
The minister believed that the geological and mineral sectors
have fine prospects for bringing an economic boom to Angola.
</P>
<P>
Angola is rich in such minerals as diamond, iron, gold and
copper, he said, adding that tapping these resources will make
the industry a pillar in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has made a preliminary plan for the
industry, with the first phase focusing on iron mines, to be
followed by the development of phosphate, mineral water, copper
and other minerals, Samondo noted.
</P>
<P>
Angola's mineral industry has been devastated by long years of
civil war, and the key issue for restoring the production is
capital, which is now in dire need.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Angola has reached an agreement
with the Southern African Development Community (SADC) member
states to promote regional cooperation in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Samondo also revealed that his ministry is now undertaking a
comprehensive survey on the country's mineral resources, which
will lead to minute professional maps for future investment in
the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
