<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Living Standard Drops, Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada is the only major
industrial country this decade to have suffered a drop in its
standard of living, according to an economic think tank here.
</P>
<P>
The living standard in Canada plummeted from second to that of
the United States to seventh place over the 1989-96 period, the
Center for Study of Living Standards says in a soon-to-be-released
report.
</P>
<P>
Canada was the only one of the group of 13 industrial countries
to experience an absolute fall in living standards, the study
notes.
</P>
<P>
Its gross domestic product (GDP) per capita dropped 0.4 percent
in the seven-year period, while the average growth in per capita
GDP for the 13 countries was 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
This fall in per capital GDP has pushed Canada from the ranks
of wealth per individual to seventh behind the U.S., Norway,
Japan, Germany, Denmark and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, Canada's per capita GDP was 81.7 percent of that in
the U.S. By 1996, it slipped to 76.7 percent of the U.S. figure.
</P>
<P>
On the productivity front, Canada's performance was equally
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
The country's productivity rose only 4.3 percent over the
period. This was the smallest increase among the 13 countries. The
average increase for the group was 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study says Canada's economic problems during the period are
largely of its own making.
</P>
<P>
One of the major reasons for the results is the severe impact
of Canada's monetary policy during the period when the Bank of
Canada conducted a high-interest rate policy to combat inflation.
</P>
<P>
The high interest rates led to the Canadian economy
underperforming compared with other countries, the study says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
