<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Udovenko Elected New President of UN General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The General Assembly
of the United Nations today elected Hennadiy Udovenko, minister
for foreign affairs of Ukraine, president of the it 52nd session.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko has held the post of minister for foreign affairs
since September 1994. Prior to being assigned to this post, he was
Ukraine's ambassador to Poland form 1992 to 1994. He also holds
the diplomatic rank of ambassador extraordinary and
plenipotentiary.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko, 66, is a career diplomat who had worked for many
years in the service of his country and for the United Nations,
both in New York and in Geneva. From 1980 to 1995, he was
Ukraine's deputy foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
From 1985 to 1992, as the permanent representative of Ukraine
to the United Nations, Udovenko served in various capacities on
several intergovernmental bodies within the United Nations. In
July 1985, he served as the president of the United Nations
Security Council. He was vice-president of the 46th session of the
General Assembly, chairman of the Special Political Committee at
the 18th Special Session of the General Assembly. He was chairman
of the Second Committee at the 42nd session of the General
Assembly and of the same committee at the 15th Special Session of
the General Assembly. From 1989 to 1991, he chaired the sessions
of the Economic and Social Council as its vice-president.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure as the permanent representative of Ukraine to
the United Nations, Udovenko was also the vice-chairman of the
United Nations Special Committee against Apartheid. In that
capacity, his contribution to the eradication of apartheid was
internationally recognized. On many occasions, he headed or was a
member of the committee's delegation to various seminars,
symposiums and other international forums.
</P>
<P>
He also participated in many meetings held within the
framework of the Committee on the Exercise of the Inalienable
Rights of the Palestinian People.
</P>
<P>
He has been actively involved in several other organs and
bodies -- both within and outside the United Nations system --
dealing with political, economic and financial issues, as well
as development, the environment and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1931, Udovenko graduated from Taras Shevchenko Kyiv
University in 1954. After obtaining his degree in international
relations, he took a postgraduate course at the Ukrainian
Scientific and Research Institute of Economics of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko speaks English, Russian, Polish and some French. In
1995, he was awarded the Honorary Award of the President of
Ukraine in recognition of his personal contribution to the
development of Ukraine' foreign policy. He is married and had a
grown-up daughter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0070 </DOCNO>
