<HEADLINE> Air Crash Rescue in Namibia Enters Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A multi-nation search
operation for two planes which collided in mid-air off the
Namibian coast has ended its second day with little success.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Windhoek, the Namibian capital
said, so far only one unidentified body has been recovered from
the sea.
</P>
<P>
An American air force cargo plane, with nine people on board,
and a German military aircraft, with 24 passengers, crashed off
the northern Namibian coast late on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The planes went down in an area 50 kilometers south of the
mouth of the Kunene river at the Angolan-Namibian border, and 90
kilometers off the coast.
</P>
<P>
The search and rescue mission has managed to recover more
debris belonging to the German aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Seven more planes from German and American air force have
arrived in Windhoek, to assist the recovery of any wreckage,
bodies and survivors.
</P>
<P>
Two other German aircraft have left the Gabonese capital,
Libreville, and will fly to the searching area.
</P>
<P>
Radio Namibia said the search is being complicated by bad
weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
