<HEADLINE> Zambia Determined to Protect National Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official
declared here today that the Zambian government is determined to
protect its industries from subsidized imports, according to
Zambia News Agency Zana.
</P>
<P>
After a conducted tour with two visiting Tanzanian deputy
ministers in the capital, Ackim Nkole, deputy minister of
commerce, trade and industry, said no more industries in Zambia
will be closed down as measures are being put in place to arrest
the situation.
</P>
<P>
Many companies in the manufacturing sector in particular have
been bankrupt since the country's economic liberalization in
early 1990s, due to "unfair competition" from foreign goods,
President Frederick Chiluba was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The government is doing everything possible to ensure that
local manufacturing companies are protected from cheap subsidized
imports," said Nkole.
</P>
<P>
He cited the government's ban on the importation of wheat
flour as one of the many measures to be taken to protect local
producers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Zambia issued an order with immediate
effect to ban the importation of wheat flour on grounds that the
country's milling capacity can meet the demands of its
population.
</P>
<P>
The government has complained that Zambia is being turned into
a "dumping ground" for cheap goods from neighboring countries
such as South Africa and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Local industrialists and manufacturing organizations have
urged the government to counteract and slap reasonable duty on
all imported goods into the country to protect its national
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
