<HEADLINE> Intl. Tide-Watching Festival Opens in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 40,000 Chinese and
foreign tourists attended today's opening of the 1997 China Intl.
Qiantang River Tide-Watching Festival in Haining, east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Watching the tides on the Qiantang River during mid-Autumn has
been traditional for local people in Haining for 800 years. The
tradition evolved into an international in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Qian Mancheng said the tide-watching site, one of the
province's 10 major tourism sites has attracted nearly 1.7 million
people from both at home and abroad since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The annual festivals have greatly enhanced local economic
development and Haining exported goods valued at over 2.8 billion
to over 60 foreign countries and regions in 1996 alone.
</P>
<P>
The city is home to over 190 foreign-funded enterprises with
total assets of over 250 million yuan. 
</P>
