<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, September 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia today decided to take several
stringent measures to deal with the haze, which has enveloped the
whole country since June and worsened in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
The measures decided by the cabinet today include a ban on all
forms of open burning and checks to be carried out by the police
and army open burning, Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat
said. The relevant agencies have been asked to enforce the law
strictly and impose hefty fines against those engaged in open
burning, Mohamed said at a news conference
here. (Malaysia-Haze-Measures)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab economic ministers opened the 60th regular
session of the Arab Economic and Social Council at the Arab League
headquarters here today to discuss economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The two-day talks, chaired by Tunisia, will focus on a 15-item
agenda and executive steps to set up the projected pan-Arab free
trade zone by 1998 as a prelude to the common
market. (Egypt-AL-Economic Ministers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Norway's minority Labor government will resign
next month after losing support in Monday's general election that
unsettled the Norwegian currency unit krone, and the stock and
bond markets, according to the press here today.
</P>
<P>
The next Norwegian prime minister will be Christian Democratic
Party leader Kjell Magne Bondevik, 50, a veteran legislator who
plans to form a tri-party coalition with the Center and Liberal
Left parties.
</P>
<P>
Bondevik will have his work cut out later, but the two parties
he selected to be the coalition partners still hold different
stands on key issues. (Norway-New Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
