<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reemployment To Be Handled Seriously: Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Delegates to the on-going
Party congress agreed that it is an effective way to reemploy
redundant and laid-off workers by assigning them to the service
trades.
</P>
<P>
The delegates urged practical measures to be taken to reduce
unemployment, a worsening problem to many firms which are going to
be merged or go bankrupt as a result of the deepening reforms.
</P>
<P>
State-owned businesses have so far laid off approximately
ten million workers.
</P>
<P>
But Sources say another 70 million are to compete for jobs in
the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000). Together with 15
million workers diverted from state-owned businesses, the supply
of total labor force will exceed demand in a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
However, maintaining a specific unemployment rate can offer a
loose environment for continued reforms in the state sector, as
well as opportunities for laid-off workers to get new jobs
provided there is a complete social security system, said Wen
Shizhen, governor of Liaoning province where state-owned
businesses are concentrated and the number of laid-off workers
topped most other areas.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that special attention should be paid to four aspects:
promote the change of concept of choosing jobs, develop employment
channels, organize the training of the laid-off workers for new
employment, and improve the labor market.
</P>
<P>
Liu Hongren, vice chairman of the Shandong Provincial Committee
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, added
that the state-owned enterprises and the government should not be
solely responsible for providing jobs only.
</P>
<P>
The delegates gave full appreciation of the achievements China
made in reemploying redundant and laid-off workers in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.5 million laid-off workers were reemployed in 1996
and meanwhile about 22 provinces, regions and municipalities have
worked out specific methods for reemployment.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 4,000 employment agencies have been set up across
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
