<HEADLINE> New Topic on an Old Lane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Zhuanta Lane, less than one
kilometer from Zhongnanhai, the headquarters of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) and central government, is the oldest
residential street in Beijing, the national capital.
</P>
<P>
These days, the ongoing 15th National Congress of CPC has
become a constant topic of conversation amongst residents living
on the lane which is known for towers built in the Yuan Dynasty
(1271-1368) and centuries old trees.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Jianguo, an employee of the Capital Steel Works, and his
family are concerned about the restructuring of state-owned
enterprises. "My company has over 200,000 employees, and the fate
of the firm directly relates to the life of its workers," said
Zhong.
</P>
<P>
"Clarification of the direction for restructuring state firms
in Jiang Zemin's report made me feel better," said Zhong.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yichao, a local resident and retired teacher, said that
"Jiang's report greatly encouraged teachers since he called for
more respect for teachers and placing priority on education."
</P>
<P>
Xie Shimin, who retired from the Beijing Higher People's Court
and lives at the No.86 Courtyard, told Xinhua: "Jiang carefully
detailed legislative work in his report.
</P>
<P>
"China must reinforce its legislative sector and establish a
healthy and complete socialist legal system as the guarantee for
economic development and restructuring state-owned enterprises."
</P>
<P>
Feng Zhi'an, governor of Hebei Province under the old regime
and an anti-Japanese military leader, also lived on the lane. Feng
died years ago in Taiwan, but his grandson Feng Yongpeng still
lives on the lane. He said that his grandfather's last will was to
be buried in his hometown. He noted that his grandfather's request
has not been fulfilled due to the present cross-Straits separation.
</P>
<P>
"All Chinese people hope that the reunification of the
motherland will be realized at the earliest possible date, and
Jiang has outlined a clear direction for tackling the complicated
Taiwan Question. I believe that my grandfather's will will
eventually come true," said Feng.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianju, a restaurant manager, said: "The congress has
convinced me that the country's reform and opening will not
change. It has also encouraged the further development of the
private sector." 
</P>
</TEXT>
