<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Officials Arrested for Involving Financial Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Prosecutors today arrested one
current and four former officials of a major Japanese securities
brokerage for allegedly paying off a corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office said those
arrested are suspected of passing on some 79 million yen (660,000
U.S. dollars) of the brokerage's profits in 1995 to Ryuichi Koike.
</P>
<P>
The arrestees included Hidekuni Lyama, a former senior managing
director of Yamaichi Securities Co., and the four others were also
related to the securities operation, one of the largest in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Koike, a notorious racketeer known as "sokaiya" in the Japanese
language, is also a major suspect of another illegal payoff
scandal involving Nomura Securities Co. and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors issued a fresh arrest warrant today to Koike,
who already has been in police custody.
</P>
<P>
Investigation indicated that Koike opened an account at
Yamaichi in June 1994 through a real estate company owned by his
younger brother and became the company's "special shareholder."
</P>
<P>
Then, Koike asked the brokerage to undertake illegal
discretionary trading on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
He demanded compensation from Yamaichi in December 1994 after
the discretionary trading resulted in losses totalling some 30
million yen (250,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi reimbursed Koike, through company officials, for the
losses with the profits it gained from futures trading on the
Singapore International Money Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Payoff to a "special shareholder" is banned under Japan's
Commercial Code, and the reimbursement of stock transaction losses
and discretionary securities trading are prohibited under the
Securities and Exchange Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
