<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Completes Declaration of Ivory Stockpile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has already declared
its ivory stockpile to the Convention On International Trade In
Endangered Species (CITES) Secretariat and can start selling when
conditional trade resumes next March, said the Zimbabwean
Minister of Mines, Evironment and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Mines, Evironment and Tourism Simon
Moyo said in a statement yesterday that Zimbabwe made the
declaration just before the CITES conference held in Harare in
June this year.
</P>
<P>
The statement was provoked by reports emanating from Geneva
which suggested that Zimbabwe had not registered its ivory with
CITES.
</P>
<P>
During the 10th CITES conference in June this year, it was
agreed that all countries wishing to trade in ivory, when trade
resumed, would have to register their stocks with the CITES
secretariat before Setember 17.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said in the statement that in its proposal to CITES,
Zimbabwe declared it had 33.4 tonnes of ivory in its stores.
According to the statement, the Zimbabwean government asked to
trade 20 tonnes of its ivory with Japan. Another 8.8 tonnes and
a further 4.6 tonnes were declared for a buy-out arrangement and
for sale to the local ivory carving industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
