<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Entitled to Check Subsidized Imports: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market For
Southern and Eastern Africa (COMESA) said here today Zambia, one
of its members, has the right to check the dumping of subsidized
imports.
</P>
<P>
COMESA acting Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said if Zambia
has proved that some imports into the country are
subsidized by the exporting country, it has the right, under the
World Trade Organization and COMESA provisions, to retaliate to
ensure that local industries are protected.
</P>
<P>
He said that when such proof is made, Zambia like any other
country, will be free to impose higher tariffs on such products
found to be subsidized and competing unfairly with local
products.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha was responding to outcries by Zambian manufacturing
industries that Zambia's over liberalization of economy has given
them unfair competition with subsidized imports that have flooded
the market, mostly from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
One major example is the recent closure of Dunlop Tire Company
after failing to cope with subsidized tires from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
To protect local milling companies, Zambia recently imposed a
ban on the importation of wheat flour into the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
