<HEADLINE> Expert Tries to Re-introduce Rhino into Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A rhino expert has arrived
in Uganda from Britain to assess the possibility of reintroducing
rhinos in the country which got extinct in the mid 1980s.
reported the local daily, The New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
Rob Brett, consultant for the newly formed rhino fund Uganda
was quoted as saying that he will take a month looking at various
areas in Uganda with a view of identifying the most suitable area
in terms of habitat and security for the rhinos.
</P>
<P>
Brett has been funded by the London Zoo to undertake the study
as part of a contribution to the rhino fund.
</P>
<P>
Two species of rhinos lived previously in the north of the
Nile area in Uganda, the black rhino in Murchiaon Falls
(northwestern Uganda) and Kidepo Walley (northeastern Uganda)
national parks and the northern white rhino in Ajia Wildlife
Reserve in west Nile area.
</P>
<P>
White rhinos were introduced in northern Murchison Falls
National Park in the 1960s. Uganda was one of five counties in
the world that was home to the northern white rhino that numbered
100 in 1968. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
