<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Declares Ivory Stockpile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has already declared
its ivory stockpile to the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) secretariat and can start selling when
conditional trade resumes next March.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Mines, Environment and Tourism Simon Moyo said
yesterday in a statement Zimbabwe made the declaration just
before the CITES conference held in June this year in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The minister's statement was provoked by reports emanating
from Geneva which suggested that Zimbabwe had not registered its
ivory with CITES.
</P>
<P>
The country would have been forced to make a last ditch effort
to beat today's deadline, if it was to dispose of its huge
stockpile of ivory.
</P>
<P>
During the 10th CITES conference, it was agreed that all
countries wishing to trade in ivory, when trade resumed, would
have to register their stocks with the secretariat by today.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said in the statement that in its proposal to CITES,
Zimbabwe declared it had 33.4 tons of ivory in its stores.
</P>
<P>
The government asked to trade 20 tons of its ivory with Japan.
Another 8.8 tons and a further 4.6 tons were declared for a
buy-out arrangement and for sale to the local ivory carving
industry.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has detailed data on all stocked tusks. If stocks
were not registered, it would be assumed they did not exist, and
consequently no trade in them could be undertaken.
</P>
<P>
Moyo promised to ensure Zimbabwe fulfilled trade requirements
in all three categories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
