<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Ruler Makes Reassurance on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state
general Sani Abacha has assured Nigerians that his military
administration will quit office on October 1 next year as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
While receiving periodic reports from the Tranistion
Implementation Committee (TIC) in the capital Abuja Tuesday,
Abacha said the military government was committed to the
implementation of the transition program to enthrone enduring
democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
The TIC reports on the transition to civil rule program
covered October 1 last year and June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
TIC Chairman Mamman Nasir said earlier his committee was
satisfied with the activities of the National Electoral
Commission of Nigeria (NECON).
</P>
<P>
NECON had, during the period, registered voters and conducted
the local government elections.
</P>
<P>
Some amendments have been made in the three-year transition
program, with the date of state governor and assembly elections,
for example, changed from the third quarter of this year to next
year.
</P>
<P>
Abacha has repeatedly said his administration would usher in
democracy in 1998.
</P>
<P>
But according to observers, what Abacha said Tuesday would be
the first time he pointedly promised the administration would
hand over power to an elected government in 1998.
</P>
<P>
This seems to be helpful in clearing the doubts surrounding
his presumed intention to contest next year's presidential
election. 
