<HEADLINE> Zambia Opposed to Outside Interference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambian president Frederick
Chiluba has said that no country has the right to dictate to
another sovereign state the mode of democracy it should follow.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted him as telling here on Tuesday
a visiting delegation of the Commonwealth Parliamentary
Association (CPA) that democracies in the world differ and it is
not right for other countries to impose their democratic style on
others.
</P>
<P>
"The British colonial system left us with the notion that only
governments of coalition could work in Africa," he told the
parliamentarian delegation from CPA branch in Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Today in Zambia our friends are crying for a coalition
government. To them democracy is only when they are in office.
When they are removed, it is not democracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the government will however continue to dialog
and interact with serious opposition parties but not at the whim
of ourside pressure.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also regretted the failure of peace in Angola despite
the peace accord signed in Lusaka in 1994 by the Angolan
government and the opposition National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA). 
</P>
