<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM Calls for Arab Coordination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign
Minister Fayez Tarawneh who is on a two-day visit to Saudi
Arabia today called on the Arab world to coordinate and strengthen
mutual trust to press Israel to return the occupied Arab land.
</P>
<P>
Getting back the Arab land occupied by Israel needs Arab
coordination based on mutual trust, Tarawneh said while holding
talks with Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdel-Aziz in Saudi
western coast city of Jedda, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh's talks with the Saudi crown prince focused on an
assessment of peace crisis caused by the hardline stances of the
Israeli government led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He said the matter needed "a comprehensive assessment between
the Arab brothers," noting that his country was coordinating
with Syria, Egypt and the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on Israel to end the closure policy
against the Palestinian people, to unblock Palestinian funds and
lift the siege imposed on Palestinian towns.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh is accompanying Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan Ibn
Talal on an official visit to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Press Agency said Prince Hassan also discussed with
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdel-Aziz on bilateral relations and the latest developments on
the Arab, Islamic and international arenas in light of the
shuttle visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the two sides tackled the possibility of
pushing forward the stalemated Middle East peace mission
according to the limited improvement achieved during Albright's
visit to the region, which took her to Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas, Syria, Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Jordan and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Prince Hassan, who arrived in Jedda Tuesday, is due to
conclude his Saudi trip later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
