<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strict Measures Ordered to Tackle Haze in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today decided
to take several stringent measures to deal with the haze, which
has enveloped the whole country since June and worsened in the
last few days.
</P>
<P>
The measures decided by the cabinet today include a ban on all
forms of open burning and checks to be carried out by the police
and army open burning, Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat said.
</P>
<P>
The relevant agencies have been asked to enforce the law
strictly and impose hefty fines against those engaged in open
burning, Mohamed, who is also National Disaster Relief Management
Committee chairman, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said the Fire and Rescue Services Department has been
ordered to immediately put out any open burning spotted.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also decided that cloud-seeding which started two
weeks ago will be carried out more often, covering a wider area
and not confined to areas where the haze is serious.
</P>
<P>
He said it has also been decided that the Royal Malaysian Air
Force (RMAF) will be directly involved in cloud-seeding.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also asked the Treasury to approve funds for the
RMAF to buy cloud-seeding equipment to be fitted to the aircraft
used for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet agreed that if the air pollutant index (API)
touches 250 and above, all land clearing and earthworks will be
stopped, Mohamed said.
</P>
<P>
He said schools would be closed when the index touches 400
while a state of emergency would be declared by Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad when the level deteriorates to 500.
</P>
<P>
Under the Malaysian API, readings between 0-50 are classified
as good, 51-100 as moderate, 101-200 as unhealthy, 201-300 as very
unhealthy and 301-500 as hazardous.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to an Environment Department statement,
the air quality throughout Malaysia has improved in most areas
compared to yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The air quality indicting the "hazardous" level yesterday with
an API reading of 359 in the Nilai area in the southeastern state
of Negeri Sembilan improved to the "unhealthy" level with an API
reading of 134.
</P>
<P>
The API readings of 302 and 344, also indicating "hazardous"
air quality level in Kuala Lumpur and its suburban Gombak area
respectively yesterday, were also down to the "unhealthy" level
with API readings of 139 and 116 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The air quality in other parts of the country also improved.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed said the improvement in the air quality today could be
due to the cloud-seeding carried out by the Environment
Department.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that cloud-seeding by the Indonesian authorities would
help improve the air quality further.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
