<HEADLINE> Beijing Youth Eager to Join Communist Party (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing has a total of 1.1 million Party members, excluding
those working in departments directly under the central
authorities. The membership includes over 210,000 people under the
age of 35, according to the organization department of the
municipal CPC committee.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, Beijing organizations recruited more than
44,000 new Party members, some 29,000 of those, or 67 percent of
the total, were under the age of 35. At present, some 229,000 of
360,000 people who have applied for Party membership are under 35.
</P>
<P>
The younger generation's enthusiasm for joining the CPC is
closely related to the fact that CPC organizations at all levels
have attached great importance to education and guidance of the
young, said Wang Liping, deputy division chief of the municipal
organization department.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out that "China's reform and opening-up drive,
economic development and social stability have also had a positive
influence on the young."
</P>
<P>
When comparing the conditions of the Chinese society before and
after the adoption of the reform and opening-up policies, the
younger generation has quite naturally reached the conclusion that
China's development and prosperity rely on the leadership of a
strong communist party, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
"The comparison greatly enhances their confidence in the
Party," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Young students who are moved and inspired by the exemplary
roles played by fellow students who are Party members are actively
applying for Party membership, according to Hou.
</P>
<P>
Hou cited an example of two undergraduate classes in the School
of International Relations. He said 14 of the top 20 students were
Party members.
</P>
<P>
He said that the example set by student Party members inspired
over 90 percent of students in the two classes to apply for Party
membership prior to graduation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
