<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Called to Continue Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today called on Indonesia to continue restructuring its
economic sector despite its achievements in keeping the rupiah's
fluctuation in check.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary for Indonesia to keep on taking such measures,
IMF Deputy Managing Director Stanley Fischer told the press after
meeting with President Soeharto here.
</P>
<P>
However, Fischer did not say what measures the IMF is expecting
Indonesia to take.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the IMF's opinion on the Indonesian rupiah's
depreciation against the U.S. dollar, Fischer praised the measures
the Indonesian government has taken so far.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the government's announcement on Tuesday that it
will postpone and review 106 trillion rupiah (about 35.6 billion
U.S. dollars) worth of development projects financed by the state
budget, state-owned companies and private enterprises, calling it
"an important step" on the road to stability.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the government should also take other
measures to save the country from a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah was traded at about 2,950 to the dollar,
compared to about 2,450 before the speculative attacks on it in
early July.
</P>
<P>
Speculative attacks have shaken most Southeast Asian currencies
following the devaluation of the Thai baht on July 2. The rupiah
has declined by over 20 percent since then.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources here, President Soeharto Tuesday
criticized the IMF for its slow action in helping Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) members deal with the region's
recent currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with a local banker, the president expected the world
body to deregulate its complicated procedures to accelerate its
mission to help needy countries.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto also complained about the attitude of industrialized
countries in anticipating financial upheavals.
</P>
<P>
He called on the developed countries in the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) to lend a helping hand to the
grouping's less developed members, in their effort to overcome the
current currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It is high time now for APEC to translate and apply its
partnership through, for instance, the establishment of a standby
loan system to tackle the ongoing monetary crisis hitting the less
developed nations in APEC," the president was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
