<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grass-roots Democracy Being Promoted in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that about one-fifth of the village
heads in China have been replaced in every election, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
The village committees are responsible mainly for making major
decisions, improving democratic supervision, and keeping the
villagers informed of political activities and financial affairs
in the villages, Doji Cering said.
</P>
<P>
"Around the turn of the century, a self-management system is
expected to be established in all villages across the country," he
said. As for the urban areas, the workers' conference is a major
grass-roots democratic unit, he added.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 290,000 enterprises, or 85 percent of the
total in the country, have established workers' conferences,
according to Zhang Dinghua, vice president of the All-China
Federation of Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
Major tasks of the conference include deliberations and
approval of the factory plans, examination of the financial
management, and a general evaluation of all officials.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprises are gaining a higher degree of self-management as
the socialist market economy progresses, Zhang said, adding that
"as a result, the role of leading executives in the enterprises
are increasingly important."
</P>
<P>
Zhang called for the function of the conference to be increased
so as to provide an effective way to check corruption or abuse of
power.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, all publicly-owned enterprises across the
country will carry out an annual democratic evaluation of their
executives, and so far this has been adopted in a total of 100,000
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, the shareholders' conference will not replace the
workers' conference which plays the role of democratic management,
despite a possible shareholding system to be introduced in
state-owned businesses, Zhang noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grass-roots Democracy Being Promoted in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Promotion of democracy at
grass-roots units in China is a major task for the on-going
political restructuring, and whether it can be realized or not has
a vital bearing on the country's long-term stability and the
people's interests, a Party congress delegate from the Chinese
Ministry of Civil Affairs said here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin's report to the ongoing 15th National Party
Congress stressed the work to improve the system of democratic
election at the grass-roots units in China and increase the
worker's participation in reforms and management of enterprises,
and this has aroused heated discussions among the
delegates, according to Doji Cering, minister of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Grass-roots democracy is mainly manifested in the elections of
village committees in rural China, and the workers' conference in
urban China, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, the overwhelming majority of the provinces across
the country have carried out at least two rounds of elections.
</P>
<P>
Over 90 percent of the farmers have participated in the
elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
"On spotting any violations of law in the process, the farmers
usually ask the press or law firms for help," said Doji Cering.
</P>
<P>
Usually, two candidates who run for the head of the
village committee make policy speeches prior to the elections,
he added.
</P>
<P>
From time to time, they answer questions from the villagers and
each villager cast a vote, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With the democratic election, the overall competence of the
village heads has improved, and a group of young farmers good at
managing farm production have taken the leading posts of the
villages, replacing those who are conservative," Doji Cering said,
stressing that "this has contributed greatly to the stability and
development of the rural areas."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
