<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso,
recovering slowly in the past few days, today fell to another
record low of 32.807 pesos against the U.S. dollar amid rising
fears of political uncertainty in the country.
</P>
<P>
This new average exchange rate between the peso and the dollar
was 1.38 percent lower than Tuesday's 32.36 pesos recorded in the
Philippine Dealing System, the country's electronic currency
exchange system.
</P>
<P>
The peso has so far depreciated 24.3 percent since the central
bank allowed it to fluctuate in a wider band on July 11 in face of
relentless international speculative attacks against the local
currency.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the latest slump in the peso's value to
mounting concerns over prolonged political instability as a result
of raging debates over amendments to the country's existing
constitution.
</P>
<P>
They said many hoped to buy more dollars before the September
21 anti-charter change rally organized by the Catholic Church and
former President Corazon Aquino.
</P>
<P>
A row over efforts by President Fidel Ramos' supporters to
change the charter so Ramos can run for a second term has set the
government in a confrontation with the Catholic Church and the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Other dampers included rising demand for the dollar by local
businesses to import goods for the forthcoming Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
