<HEADLINE> Pak PM Condoles death of Five Iranian Cadets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
spoke on phone for over 15 minutes today to Iranian President
Seyed Mohammad Khatami to condole over the death of five Iranian
personnel who were killed this morning in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed his full sympathy to the families of the
deceased and shared their sorrow, according to an official
statement issued by Foreign Office here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He also assured that his government "will investigate the
incident and do its best to arrest the culprits who deserve the
highest condemnation."
</P>
<P>
This incident should not adversely affect relations between the
two countries, which have deep roots in history, culture and
religion, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he looked forward to meeting the
president of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Six persons, including five Iranian Air Force trainees, were
killed and one injured this morning when three unidentified gunmen
fired upon them in Rawalpindi, the sister city of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan Defense Ministry is now making arrangements to
send the bodies of the trainees back to Iran, official sources
said.
</P>
<P>
According to unconfirmed reports, police have arrested two
persons suspected of involvement in the killing.  
</P>
