<HEADLINE> China to Reform Structure of Government Institutions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua)-- The number of ministries and
administrative bodies under the State Council has dropped from
68 to 59 and 56 non-permanent central government institutions have
been abolished since 1992, said a senior official from the
Ministry of Personnel.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhijian, vice-minister and deputy director of the
Committee on Organizational Structure under the CPC Central
Committee, said the number of personnel in government institutions
at different levels has been cut down from 9.25 million to 7.25
million, down by two million people.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said China had carried out reform of the structure of
central and local government institutions from 1993 to 1996. The
size of the government has been kept within the limits, with
reduction in the number of institutional organizations.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the establishment of government
departments, the personnel composition and operational structure
still cannot meet the requirements of the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The size of the government is still very large in general, he
said, leaving it a pressing and arduous task in deepening
structural reform of government institutions.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 41 ministries under the State Council and
an average of 53 government departments at the provincial level.
The number of government institutions under a medium-sized city
and a county reaches 46 and 28, respectively.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the current Party congress five days
ago, Jiang Zemin pointed out that China's government institutions
have still been plagued by "unwieldy organization, overstaffing,
failure to separate the functions of the government from those of
enterprises and serious bureaucracy."
</P>
<P>
"The fact that Jiang Zemin's report to the congress has taken
the reform of government organizational structure as one of the
important component parts of political restructuring shows that
the CPC Central Committee has attached great importance to
structural reform and its determination to push ahead political
restructuring," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He said the structural reform at present focuses on the
transformation of government functions and the separation of the
functions of the government from those of enterprises, handling
well relations between the government and the enterprises, market
and the society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Structure of Government Institutions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has a dozen of departments on economic management under
the State Council, outgrowing that in developed countries. This is
the outcome of the planned economy, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The next step of readjustment of government institutions is to
reduce the number of these departments and make some of them
economic entities without government functions.
</P>
<P>
On readjusting institutions of the local governments, Zhang
said, continued efforts will be made to cut the size of staff
working in poverty-stricken counties and townships in a bid to
alleviate the burden of the local people, he said, adding this is
a major measure to help people in poor areas to shake off poverty
by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Today, China still has 592 poverty-stricken counties, with a
combined poverty-stricken population of 60 million. Reform of
administrative structure is an important aspect of the structural
reform. The state is to work out a law on administrative
organizational structure, with the aim of legalizing the
establishment of government institutions and its management, he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the streamlining of government institutions should not
be conducted in a simple way. Macro-economic control and
law-enforcement departments should be strengthened to meet the
requirements of a market economy, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the personnel of law enforcement
departments have expanded by 200,000, the taxation departments by
200,000 and the industrial and commercial departmens by over
100,000.
</P>
<P>
How to properly arrange the redundant staff who have been
laid-off remains the most difficult task in the institutional
reform. All localities should explore new ways in accordance with
their own conditions, including expanding the service trade, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
