<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Passes Bill Against Party Defection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 17 (Xinhua) -- An anti-defection bill,
which aims to prevent MPs from deserting their own parties and
thus bring stability to Nepal's politics, has been unanimously
approved by the Lower House of Nepal, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
MPs from the ruling Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML) and the National Democratic Party (RPP)
and those from the main opposition Nepali Congress voted
overwhelmingly for the bill Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Upper House passed the bill on August 29.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, a member will be considered defecting when he
or she resigns from the party he or she was elected from, or takes
membership of another party, or forms his or her own party without
fulfilling the requirements or violating party whips.
</P>
<P>
And once the parliament leaders make public the notice of
defection issued by the party concerned, the term of the MP will
automatically be terminated and the position considered vacant,
according to the bill.
</P>
<P>
Such defecting members will be given 15 days to justify their
action, which will be reviewed by the leaders of the parliament
before action is taken against them.
</P>
<P>
But he or she will not be considered defecting when joining a
party formed by 40 percent of either the working committee members
or the parliamentary party committee members, the bill decides.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, recalcitrant MPs have been the cause of political
instability in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Things became worse after a hung parliament appeared in the
mid-term election in 1994, where no single party held a majority.
</P>
<P>
In the past seven years, MPs either refused to obey the whip of
their parliamentary leaders or left their own parties, joined the
opposition and abstained or voted against their governments,
causing the fall of four of the five governments.
</P>
<P>
The anti-defection bill, registered for discussion during the
11th session of the parliament, was passed down to the current
session because the last was plagued by confidence motions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
