<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan is expected to receive more than 75 million
U.S. dollars of European aid this year, the Jordan Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The European Council of Ministers decided to allocate 15
million dollars of additional aid to Jordan Monday, the paper
quoted Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Development Affairs
Jawad Anani as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both sides reached an agreement last April under which Jordan
will receive 50 million dollars of aid from Europe.
</P>
<P>
Anani, who just concluded visits to six European countries
Tuesday, said some European countries had pledged more than 10
million dollars extra aid for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Algeria signed here Tuesday two agreements
on prevention of dual taxation and cooperation in customs affairs
and legislation, the Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both sides signed a protocol designed for promoting
bilateral industrial and commercial cooperation through setting up
joint projects.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has concluded contracts with Iraq to sell it
more than 83 million U.S. dollars worth of food and medicine, the
Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that 35 Jordanian corporations were involved in
the contracts signed within the framework of the U.N.-Iraqi
oil-for-food deal which allows Baghdad to sell up to 2 billion
dollars of oil over six months to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The goods under the contracts include soap, detergents and
table salt, and more Jordanian bids to sell other goods to Iraq
are under discussion by Iraq and U.N. agencies concerned,
according to the Amman Chamber of Industry.
</P>
<P>
It disclosed that Jordanian pharmaceutical firms are currently
striving to sign contracts with Iraq to sell it 210 million
dollars worth of medicine and hoped that they could get a good
share of the transaction.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese housing problem has turned into a crisis
that transcended low income groups to hit middle income workers,
according to a latest report by a leading commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the Beirut-based Fransabank, one of the
leading commercial banks here, said that the middle income
workers make up 55 percent of Lebanon's labor force. Low income
groups live on 500 U.S. dollars or less a month while middle
income workers live on 500 to 2,000 dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
The report said that on the other hand, 60,000 to 100,000
housing units with 11 million to 15 million square meters
lay empty because developers overestimated the purchasing power
of the public who do not have access to long-term loans.
</P>
<P>
It called on the government to develop a secondary mortgage
market to solve the housing crisis and keep up with neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The primary mortgage market in Lebanon comprises 300 million
to 400 million dollars of extended and available loans. These
loans are provided by the state-owned housing bank and other six
private banks that extend 10-year loans at 11 to 13 percent
interest, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, it said that the amount of available loans does not
cover more than 7 percent of the 5.5 million to 7 million dollars
market value of the empty apartments. The loans are not long
enough and remain relatively expensive.
</P>
<P>
The report said a secondary mortgage market, which will provide
more liquidity and bring down mortgage prices, has a good chance
of succeeding in Lebanon because the country has a developed and
deregulated capital market and interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
