<HEADLINE> Party Congress as Seen by Ordinary Chinese (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- For Liu Ming, a middle-aged
laid-off factory worker in northeast China's Jilin Province,
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's opening speech to the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) was like a
soothing dose of tonic.
</P>
<P>
She was moved to tears while watching Jiang deliver a report on
September 12, in which he pledged that the Party and government
will take steps to better care for and accommodate the laid-off
workers, and improve the re-employment program.
</P>
<P>
"Jiang Zemin has us laid-off workers on his mind, and cares a
lot about us," said the jobless woman.
</P>
<P>
Another laid-off factory worker from Jilin, 46-year-old Zhou
Lihua, applauded Jiang's call on the broad masses of workers to
alter their frame of mind and take pains to improve their work
skills so as to adapt to demands of reform and development.
</P>
<P>
Zhou attended a training course on household affairs, was a
nurse for a mentally-retarded child and has eventually taken a
job in a vocational school after she was laid off by her
former factory.
</P>
<P>
"When I review my past experience, I think what General
Secretary Jiang said is right," said Li. "The way out for laid-off
people is to improve their own quality to adapt to the changing
situation."
</P>
<P>
Tong Fengying, who was laid off by a textile mill several years
ago, now works for a job placement agency attached to a local
women's federation.
</P>
<P>
Tong agreed with Jiang that flow of personnel and laid-off
workers is only a temporary difficulty brought on by the expansion
of enterprise reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
