<HEADLINE> Party Congress as Seen by Ordinary Chinese (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Truck drivers from a mining company associated with the Anshan
Iron and Steel Corporation, based in northeast China's Liaoning
Province, agree that Jiang's words lifted a great weight from
their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
The once-distressed drivers have plenty to smile about now.
After two months of management reform in the mining company,
drivers from many trucking teams scattered over 30 separate
production areas of the mine have been organized into a
centralized professional unit.
</P>
<P>
Some of the truck drivers, who had been accustomed to the "rice
bowl" routine, were unhappy with the strict work assignments after
the reshuffling, said Zhao Xiufen, a local Party official.
</P>
<P>
They even described the reform in their company as an effort
taken in vain. But Jiang's speech was like a key that unlocked
their minds, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The move to form a single strong unit was a wise act that
serves the long-term interests of the drivers, and after hearing
Jiang's report, they realize that, the official added.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, Qiang Ziqiang, a retired engineer from Shanghai
Aircraft Manufacturing Factory, and his wife said they are deeply
impressed by the plan proposed by the congress to develop various
forms of economic ownership for state firms while making sure
public ownership remains a dominant force.
</P>
<P>
Both are now retired workers from state-run enterprises. Their
elder son is working for a Sino-overseas joint venture, their
second son is running a business of his own after he returned from
studying abroad, and their daughter is employed at a state-owned
enterprise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
