<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Record Zero Population Growth in 2040 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is expected to see a
zero growth in its population in 2040, when it will have 205
million people if the total fertility rate continues to be kept at
3.3 percent until that time.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goal means that one woman will give birth to only
one child, it was learned here today from the Bangladesh Bureau of
Statistics (BBS).
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh will have to wait another 43 years to stabilize its
population at around 205 million," said a BBS official.
</P>
<P>
The fertility rate, which was 4.9 percent in 1990, declined to
3.4 percent in 1996 and 3.1 percent in 1997 and it will hover
around 2.2 percent in the future, the official said, adding that
it means that population growth will remain at zero percent on a
long-term basis.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dhaka Office of the U.N. Population Fund
(UNPF), Bangladesh has proven to be one of the successful
countries in the last quarter of the 20th century in terms of
population control and the contraceptive prevalence rate (CPR).
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has lowered its population growth rate from 3
percent in 1973 to 1.6 percent in 1997 while it has raised the CPR
from 8.5 percent in 1975 to 48 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But it is still much below the UNPF-recommended 68 percent to
check the rapid growth of population in the country.
</P>
<P>
The population of Bangladesh is estimated at 123.8 million in
1997, the ninth largest in the world and the sixth in Asia,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Future population growth potential in Bangladesh is very high
because of a large base of young population (below 15 years) and
women of reproductive age (15-49 years).
</P>
<P>
People below 15 years account for 43 percent of the total
population and women of reproductive age represent 46 percent of
the total female population, the official added.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft Fifth Five-Year Plan (1997-2002), Bangladesh
will see a net increase of 8.8 million in its population during
the period while by the year 2020, there will be a net growth of
42.74 million people.
</P>
<P>
Due to the population growth momentum, the number of working
age population (15-59 years) will increase from 66.6 million this
year to 80.2 million in 2010 and 109 million in 2020.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
