<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Additional Funding for Basic Scientific Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government will
allocate 60 million yuan (seven million US dollars) annually and a
total of 300 million yuan during the Ninth Five-Year Period
(1996-2000) to support training for Chinese scientists involved in
basic scientific research.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be administered by the National Training Fund
For Scientists in Basic Scientific Research. More than 90 percent
of the funds will be used to establish training bases, with the
remaining 10 percent earmarked for training of scientists involved
in major scientific projects and key branches of learning.
</P>
<P>
The State Science and Technology Commission has approved
funding for six major scientific projects, including the wide
array multi-object spectrum telescope, the Hefei National
synchronous Radiation Laboratory, and an earth mantle movement
monitoring network.
</P>
<P>
Financial assistance will also be given to six branches of
learning related to glacier cryopedology, archeology,
paleontology, paleoanthropology, fossil invertebrates, and the
classification of flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
Some 83 training bases have been established in 15 majors of 39
universities since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The fund management committee will hold a meeting in early
September to draft detailed regulations for funds distribution.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned committee is headed by academician Tang
Aoqing, who also serves as honorary chairman of the State Natural
Science Fund Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
