<HEADLINE> Time Warner, CNN Hired to Do PR for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Board of
Investment has launched a major publicity campaign with the
U.S.-based Time Warner and CNN (Cable News Network), aimed at
rebuilding foreign business and investor confidence in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The initial three-month phase of the campaign, at a cost of
nearly 3 million U.S. dollars, will deliver the message that
"Thailand is on the road to recovery" after 17.7 billion dollars
in standby rescue credit and other loans has been made available
to Thailand through the brokerage of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"We want the world to know what Thailand's problems are, what
medicine we are taking, and what the prospects for recovery are,"
a press release issued today quoted Staporn Kavitanon, secretary
general of the board, as saying. "It is no ordinary thing for a
government and people to admit mistakes, talk about how painful
recovery itself will be, and still optimistic about the future."
</P>
<P>
The publicity campaign, launched this week in Asiaweek magazine
and the Asian edition of Time magazine, revolves around a series
of three, full-page black-and-white ads, using text only to convey
the seriousness of the message.
</P>
<P>
The print campaign is accompanied by a parallel TV campaign on
CNN. Three separate ads have been created depicting in stark,
simple terms Thailand's efforts to return to normalcy and
recovery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
