<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Calls for Reexamination of Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Foreign Minister
Pitak Intrawithayanunt today called on APEC and other
international forums to reexamine the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
Opening a seminar on "the implications of the APEC process for
intra-regional trade and investment flows in Asia and the
Pacific", Pitak said, "while globalization is an undeniable
reality of modernization, the downside of globalization has also
begun to show itself."
</P>
<P>
He said, "it could be argued that a most dramatic downside of
globalization and liberalization can be seen in the economic
situation currently afflicting Thailand and some other Southeast
Asian countries."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that there should be some regional
response to the vulnerabilities faced by developing countries in
the process of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from about 20 economies in the Asia Pacific
region are attending the three-day seminar, organized by the
United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the
Pacific (ESCAP), designed to help developing countries in the
region to effectively respond to challenges and opportunities
arising from the process of globalization and regionalization.
</P>
<P>
The seminar is expected to provide an opportunity for a
systematic analysis of the topical issues such as the impact of
trade liberalization in the region, the implications for the
intra-regional trade and investment in the non-APEC countries of
the region.
</P>
<P>
In its "trade and development report 1997", launched worldwide
this week, the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development
(UNCTAD) sounds warning on globalization and advocates policies to
counter economic polarization and growing income inequality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
