<HEADLINE> Rapid Economic Growth in East Asia to Continue: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The recent currency crisis
in Southeast Asian financial markets would not stop continuing
spectacular growth in the region, Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said today.
</P>
<P>
"East Asia is going to continue to grow economically, whatever
difficulties there may have been in recent weeks in the financial
markets in some of the Southeast Asian economies," Downer said in
a speech to the Asian Business Connection in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"East Asia is going to continue to grow and in our judgment
grow strongly over the medium to long term," he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the evolution of East Asia, the world's most
influential economic region by next century, as one of the most
important influences on Australia's future.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government's recent white paper on foreign
affairs and trade has put Australia's relationship with the
Asia-Pacific region as the top priority of the country's foreign
policy agenda.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says Australia's ties with the United States,
Japan, Indonesia and China are the country's four most important
relationships.
</P>
<P>
Australia's trade performance was already highly dependent on
the East Asian region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Sixty-one percent of our exports go into East Asia. We are one
of the most East Asian oriented, most East Asian dependent
economies in the world," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Our exports in the 1996-97 financial year (ending on June 30,
1997) to East Asia were 32.5 billion US dollars. The imports were
20 billion US dollars. We are doing extraordinarily well in East
Asian markets and can do better," he added.
</P>
<P>
Australia's focus on the Asia-Pacific did not mean the
Australian federal government would ignore the foreign policy in
Europe, the United States, South America and the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
