<HEADLINE> Malaysia Red Cross Grants DPRK Famine Relief Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian Red
Crescent Society (MRCS) today presented a 10.5 million ringgit
(about 3.5 million U.S. dollars) cheque to the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) for the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Famine Relief Fund.
</P>
<P>
This was the biggest sum ever collected by the MRCS for
international humanitarian appeals, MRCS Chairman Abdul Hamid Omar
said when presenting the cheque to Johan Schaar, the IFRC's Kuala
Lumpur regional delegation head.
</P>
<P>
The money would be sent to the IFRC headquarters in Geneva,
Switzerland, for coordination before being channeled to the DPRK
Red Cross through the regional delegation concerned, he said.
</P>
<P>
The MRCS together with the Kuala Lumpur IFRC and the STAR
Publication launched a nationwide appeal to collect the fund on
August 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Hamid said the fund would be used to feed 740,000
starving children in 19 DPRK counties, to set up community clinics
and hospitals with basic drugs and medical supplies for one year
and to upgrade a three-year program of the DPRK Red Cross to cope
with emergencies and disasters.  
</P>
