<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers Start Economic, Social Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Arab economic ministers opened
the 60th regular session of the Arab Economic and Social Council
at the Arab League headquarters here today to discuss economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
The two-day talks, chaired by Tunisia, will focus on a 15-item
agenda and executive steps to set up the projected pan-Arab free
trade zone by 1998 as a prelude to the common market.
</P>
<P>
According to a resolution issued by a previous ministerial
council meeting in 1996, non-tariff barriers should be eliminated
and tariffs be gradually reduced until complete liberalization is
reached by the end of the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
Other topics on the agenda include a unified Arab economic
report, proposed amendments to the Arab Labor Organization
statutes, the opening of offices for the U.N. Industrial
Development Organization (UNIDO) in the Arab region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also discuss recommendations by the Arab
central banks and the Arab monetary institutions, the unified Arab
stand during the annual meetings of the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank, and the report on food security in the
Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Conditions in the Palestinian self-rule areas are also to be
discussed during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority sustains daily losses of
between 5 and 8 million dollars as a result of the Israeli siege,
according to Palestinian Minister of Economy Maher al Masri.
</P>
<P>
Masri, who is attending the meeting, complained of the plight
of the Palestinians under the 50-day blockade Israel imposed after
a double suicide bombing attack hit Jerusalem on July 30.
</P>
<P>
He said he will address the meeting on the damage done to the
Palestinians by the continued embargo and the PNA vision of several
issues including the setting up of an Arab free-trade zone and
inter-Arab cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
