<HEADLINE> Pakistan FM Shocked over Killing of Iranian Trainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan today expressed "profound shock and grief" over
the terrorist attack, killing five Iranian cadets in Rawalpindi,
the sister city of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"It is a tragedy that the Pakistani nation collectively mourns
in solidarity with their Iranian brethren," Gohar said in a
message.
</P>
<P>
He said "we have been profoundly shocked and grieved by the
terrorist incident in which five Iranians and a Pakistani driver
lost their precious lives."
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything to apprehend the criminals responsible
for this dastardly act," he said. "They would be meted out
exemplary punishment."
</P>
<P>
He underlined his strong resolve "not to allow any quarter to
affect Pakistan's historical and special relations with Iran."
</P>
<P>
Five Iranian Air Force trainees, who have come here for a two
month training since August, were killed along with a Pakistani
driver by some unidentified gunmen this morning.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Iranian embassy here strongly condemned the
terrorist killing, adding they are soon to issue an official
statement about the incident.
</P>
<P>
Describing the killing of Iranian Air Force Trainees as
"unfortunate", Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Siddique
Kanju told reporters that will not affect the friendly bilateral
ties between Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
After visiting the man who was wounded in the incident at a
local hospital, Kanju said "it is an act of terrorism and we must
be very conscious about it. "
</P>
<P>
Islamabad enjoys very friendly relations with Tehran and this
unfortunate incident would not affect bilateral ties, Kanju said.
</P>
<P>
"It would not affect our relations at all," he said, adding it
is pre-mature to comment on the reason for the unfortunate
incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
