<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Realistic Value for Australian Dollar: Fischer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was at
a more accurate and realistic value for exporters after slumping
to a two-year low Tuesday, acting prime minister Tim Fischer said
today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar Tuesday closed the day weaker against the
US dollar after earlier hitting a 26-month low of 71.65 US cents,
its lowest level since it reached 71.42 in mid-July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Economists here today feared an interest rate cut and a weak
outlook for commodity prices could pressure the local unit down
further to 71 US cents in the near term.
</P>
<P>
"As a consequence of that (lower dollar) we have an accurate
and more realistic value for the Australian dollar," acting prime
minister Fischer, as the prime minister John Howard has left for
the South Pacific Forum, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"It's an exporter's dollar, I am proud of that circumstance,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Movements in the exchange rate since December were the
equivalent to a new tariff of 10 percent, and that the exchange
rate was more significant than tariff settings, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
Citibank senior economist Annette Beacher said the Australian
dollar was likely to fall further in coming days with no major
local economic data due until the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
"There is not a lot of domestic data to help sway the
Australian dollar from a domestic point of view, we need some
signs of strength on the domestic front but we will not get that
until later in the year," the economist said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
