<HEADLINE> Firing Incident not Affect Ties with Iran: Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The killing of five Iranian
air force trainees by unidentified gunmen in Pakistan today was
"unfortunate" but the incident will not affect Pakistan's friendly
 ties with Iran, State Minister for Foreign Affairs Siddique Kanju
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The five Iranian air force trainees, who came here for a
two-month training in August, were shot dead by unidentified
gunmen this morning in Rawalpindi, the sister city of the
Pakistani capital.
</P>
<P>
"It is an act of terrorism and we must be very conscious about
it," Kanju told a news conference after having visited those who
were wounded in the incident with Interior Minister Shujat Hussain
at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad enjoys very friendly relations with Tehran and this
unfortunate incident would not affect bilateral ties, Kanju said.
</P>
<P>
"It would not affect our relations at all," he said, adding it
is pre-mature to comment on the reason of the unfortunate
incident.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Shujat said at a news conference that "they
were our guests from a brotherly Muslim country and we are sorry
for their killings."  
</P>
</TEXT>
