<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers: No Compromise With Government on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Jewish settlers, who moved
into the eastern Jerusalem neighborhood of Ras al-Amud and caused
a new crisis in Palestinian-Israeli relations, today denied the
report that they have reached a compromise with government to end
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, Israel Army radio reported on such a
reconciliation between the settlers and the government.
</P>
<P>
The settlers said the report was not true and insisted that the
Jerusalem Municipality has approved the building plan on the plot
in Ras al-Amud, which U.S. businessman Irving Moskowitz bought
over a decade ago, and they have right to live in this area.
</P>
<P>
The new crisis was sparked when Israeli Interior Ministry
appeals committee Sunday rejected an appeal by two Meretz Party
members to overturn the Jerusalem Municipality decision to permit
the building of 70 Jewish housing units in Ras al-Amud and three
Jewish families moved into the settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has warned of violence
if the settlers remain in Ras al-Amud. "The PNA officially holds
the Israeli government responsible for any development that will
take place unless the settlers are evicted in the coming hours,"
PNA Local Authorities Minister Saeb Erekat said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Erekat and other PNA officials said that they, in coordination
with Israel, have ensured calm among the Palestinians in and
around Jerusalem. But, they added their ability to impose
restraint was limited.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Israeli government sought ways to deal
with the Ras al-Amud crisis. Prime Minister's office Tuesday
convened an emergency meeting and decided to take a series of
measures, among them the appointment of Internal Security
Minister Avigdor Kahalani to head the team of officials dealing
with the move of Jewish settlers into the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
stressed that the government would" exhaust all the means for
talks with those involved" to find a solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
