<HEADLINE> Iran Strongly Protests Killing Students in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran today lodged a strong
protest against Pakistan over the killing of five Iranian
students by unknown gunmen in Rawalpindi in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that shortly after
the incident in the Pakistani city of Rawalpindi Wednesday
morning, the Pakistani Ambassador to Tehran Khalid Mahmood was
summoned to Iran's Foreign Ministry and a strong protest was
lodged over the incident.
</P>
<P>
Mohsen Aminzadeh, deputy foreign minister for Asia and Pacific,
protested the tragic incident and demanded an official explanation
from the government of Pakistan against the terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
Aminzadeh called for the swift arrest and punishment of the
perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
He said "if the agents of attack on the Iranian Cultural
Center in Multan and Lahore had been punished, this organized
event would not have been repeated."
</P>
<P>
Mahmood expressed his government's deep regret over the attack.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Pakistan said that the students were
attacked on their way to their place of work at Pakistan's Air
Force. Four Iranian students were killed on the spot and the fifth
died in hospital laster. Only one student survived. 
</P>
</TEXT>
