<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway's Labor Government To Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 17 (Xinhua)--Norway's minority Labor
government will resign next month after losing support in Monday's
general election that unsettled the Norwegian currency unit krone,
and the stock and bond markets, according to the press here today.
</P>
<P>
The next Norwegian prime minister will be Christian Democratic
Party leader Kjell Magne Bondevik, 50, a veteran legislator who
plans to form a tri-party coalition with the Center and Liberal
Left parties.
</P>
<P>
Bondevik will have his work cut out later, but the two parties
he selected to be the coalition partners still hold different
stands on key issues.
</P>
<P>
Since both partners did poorly in the election, the coming
Bondevik government could hold only 42 of 165 parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
The Party of Progress, led by Carl I. Hagen, came second in the
election with 15.3 percent of the votes, but it is unlikely to be
included in the coalition despite its strong showing.
</P>
<P>
It stands for more spending on the elderly and limited
immigration.
</P>
<P>
Many political observers in Norway speculate that if the
coalition of Bondevik proves too fragile, Labor could wield power
again soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
