<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenyang to Expand Memorial Hall of September 18th Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang city in northeast
China will expand a memorial hall commemorating the September 18th
Incident, a key event in the Chinese war of resistance against
Japanese aggression during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
The new Memorial Hall of the September 18th Incident in
Shenyang, capital of Liaoning Province, will cover 15,000 square
meters, much roomier than the former facility, so as to display
more cultural relics, photos and documents, said Shenyang Mayor Mu
Suixin.
</P>
<P>
The expansion project, which will cost 70 million yuan (8.4
million US dollars), will be finished before October 1999, he
announced today.
</P>
<P>
Japanese troops battled the Chinese army stationed at Shenyang
and occupied the city on September 18, 1931, signaling the start
of Japan's invasion of China.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang opened the memorial hall on September 18, 1991, at
the battlegrounds, and made it a "base for patriotic education."
</P>
<P>
The memorial hall has received more than one million Chinese
and foreign visitors since 1991, including many from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto visited the memorial
hall early this month during his visit to Shenyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Head Calls For More Multilateral Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- World Bank (WB) President James
Wolfensohn today called for more financial aid on a multilateral
level to cope effectively with currency turmoil and support
projects in developing countries, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, Wolfensohn stressed the importance of multilateral aid
by international financial organizations, including the WB,
voicing concern over recent moves by such countries as the United
States to give priority to bilateral over multilateral aid.
</P>
<P>
The WB head told Hashimoto that multilateral aid can provide
leverage for collecting additional funds.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Japan plans to cut its official development
assistance (ODA) spending by 10 percent in its fiscal 1998 budget
as part of fiscal consolidation efforts, Hashimoto, on his part,
called for the effective use of ODA.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Wolfensohn that Japan is considering providing
indirect aid by encouraging other official funds and private funds
with ODA as a core, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn is here on his way to Hong Kong where the WB and the
International Monetary Fund annual meetings will begin next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
