<HEADLINE> Singapore to Organize International Fashion Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will step up its
efforts to become a fashion capital in the region by organizing
the inaugural Singapore International Fashion Festival in October
next year, the Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB)and the
Singapore Tourist Promotion Board (STPB) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore International Fashion Festival, to be jointly
organized by the two boards, aims to position Singapore as a
fashion capital where people from the industry congregate to trade
and exchange ideas, they said.
</P>
<P>
The festival will also serve as a springboard for international
fashion houses to launch their Spring/Summer collections to the
region, the TDB and STPB said, stressing that Singapore will be
the region's window to the latest in fashion and trends.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore International Fashion Festival is designed to be
an enhanced version of the current Fashion Connections Singapore
(FCS), which has traditionally focused on fashion shows presenting
the collections of Asian and local designers and labels, the TDB
and STPB said.
</P>
<P>
The fashion festival will build on the current objectives of
the FCS, which is to provide a platform to identify young fashion
talents and for established Asian designers to showcase their
latest collections, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates on Development in Central, Western China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Delegates to the ongoing 15th
Party Congress considered the opportunity precious for China to
boost the development in its vast central and western parts, where
there are abundant natural resources and great market potentials.
</P>
<P>
During panel discussions, delegates hailed the parts in Jiang
Zemin's report delivered at the opening session of the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China on the
development strategies in the current less developed regions.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's report said that the state planned to strengthen the
support for the central and western parts by giving them priority
in arranging infrastructure and resources development projects,
encourage both Chinese and overseas investors to invest in the
regions, and further develop all forms of association and
cooperation between the eastern and the central and western parts.
</P>
<P>
Central and western China occupies 86 percent of the country's
total territory and their population accounts for 58 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
Time is now ripe for boosting its development. According to
delegates, key industrial and energy projects have been built in
these parts to tap the rich resources. The state has mapped out
preferential policies for their growth. The thriving east part has
showed the intention to explore the new market in those regions
where the labor cost is still low and consumption potentials vast.
Their geographical locations are suitable for bilateral and
multi-lateral international economic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Efforts made by these regions to boost infrastructure
construction have paid off.
</P>
<P>
Take transport construction for instance, the Nanning-Kunming
railway and the Lanzhou-Urumqi double track railway have been in
operation. The Xi'an-Ankang and south Xinjiang lines are now under
construction. A new airport in Guiyang, capital of Guizhou
Province, has been opened to flights and the expansion project of
Kunming Airport in Yunnan Province is slated to be completed late
next year.
</P>
<P>
The central and western parts also planned to foster a
contingent of new pillar industries or new economic growth
outlets.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan this year planned to invest 23.5 billion yuan in 58 key
projects.
</P>
<P>
In this year alone, the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region poured
1.7 billion yuan into building a high-quality cotton production
base.
</P>
<P>
Energy production is another fast-growth sector in these parts.
</P>
<P>
Delegates said that China's energy production footholds have
been gradually shifted westward. Shaanxi, Gansu, Ningxia,
Xinjiang and Qinghai have become China's important energy
producers. A number of state-level petrochemical, coal,
non-ferrous minerals and other raw materials production bases are
now under construction in these regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
