<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates on Development in Central, Western China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chongqing, China's newly-established municipality considered as
the pacesetter in the development of central and western China, is
making plans to accelerate the region's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Delin, secretary of the Chongqing Municipal Party
Committee, said the city has put forward three strategic programs:
</P>
<P>
-- The city will improve its comprehensive strength and help
bring about industrial and commercial growth in the central and
western parts of China;
</P>
<P>
-- In view of the fact that its rural areas are larger than the
urban districts, the municipal government will boost economic
development in both urban districts and rural areas; and
</P>
<P>
-- It will remove more people from the dam areas of the Three
Gorges Project and accelerate the economic growth there.
</P>
<P>
According to information provided by delegates to the current
congress, Guangdong has built 150 joint ventures in the central
and western parts with a total investment of 12 billion yuan.
Shanghai has invested 3.5 billion yuan in 170 projects. Zhejiang,
Fujian, Jiangsu and Shandong provinces have also invested heavily
in the regions.
</P>
<P>
Rural enterprises across China have signed 30,000 contracts
with their counterparts in these regions.
</P>
<P>
Sun Guangyuan, an assistant to the governor of Shandong
Province, said the practice of building enterprises in the central
and western parts of China by firms in coastal areas have not only
helped the under-developed areas with funds but also up-to-date
managerial expertise and marketing skills.
</P>
<P>
To boost economic development in the old revolutionary base
areas, poverty-stricken areas, border areas and areas inhabited by
ethnic minorities, over 4,000 enterprises from well-developed
parts of the countries have established businesses and opened
training courses to help develop rich local natural resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
