<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Worker-Owned State Enterprise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A medium-sized chemical
plant in Chongqing Municipality in southwest China became one of
the earliest state enterprises bought by employees when 1,200
workers spent 4.7 million yuan on the plant recently.
</P>
<P>
The purchase on June 18 of the Chongqing Jialing Chemical
Products Co. Ltd marked a shift from a form of state ownership to
collective ownership.
</P>
<P>
The plant produces potassium permanganate and potassium
hydroxide and was first in China in its field. But it almost went
bankrupt because of poor management and a failure to adapt to the
market economy. Its asset to debt ratio was 98 percent at its
worst.
</P>
<P>
So, departments decided to reform its property-holding system
and it was sold and reorganized as a modern company, with the
municipal government strongly supporting the move, and even
setting up an old-age insurance fund for the retired workers,
using profits from the property-rights transfer.
</P>
<P>
The reform has been praised by local banks, because it avoided
possible bad side effects. Because the city still has some similar
enterprises, the success of the reform may serve as an example
through its low cost and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Advocates of the reform method argue that the newly-formed
company, whose shares are owned by individual workers, is still a
form of public ownership. According to the reform plans, the
largest shareholder, or legal representative, can own about 10
percent of the total number of stocks.
</P>
<P>
Workers chose their own managers by secret ballot, greatly
encouraging them to participate in the management process. On the
very day the new company was established, there were already many
proposals from workers.
</P>
<P>
Now other state enterprises in the city are demanding that they
be allowed to follow suit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
