<HEADLINE> Preparations Made for Damming Yangtze River Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Preparations have been made to
stop the Yangtze River flow at the Three Gorges to make way
for a dam and generators.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, work on two parallel cofferdams on
both banks of the river, which will proceed in three phases, has
been moving rapidly, and 60 meters is expected to be added this
month.
</P>
<P>
The Gezhouba Group Company, which dammed the Yangtze for the
first time 16 years ago, is now in charge of this work on
the middle reaches of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The first-stage, which left two openings 460 m. and 480 m. wide
respectively in the two cofferdams, was completed in the first
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The second stage will be finished by November 3 this year. It
will leave two outlets, 130 m. and 240 m., in the cofferdams. And
the third stage, when the Yangtze is completely stopped, will be
finished by November 8.
</P>
<P>
A canal has been built to allow navigation on the Yangtze after
the Three Gorges Project cuts off the flow.
</P>
<P>
The canal is now being experimented with and is scheduled to go
into operation in October, after which all ships will pass the
Three Gorges area using that route.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
