<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Stresses Private Infrastructure in East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The private sector should
be heavily relied on to address massive infrastructure needs in
East Asia, the world's fastest growing region, a World Bank (WB)
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure is a major challenge facing most developing
countries in East Asia, if the region is to maintain a rapid
growth rate and improve living standards, Harinder Kohli, a senior
adviser with the WB, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
With projected growth for Asia at the 7-8 percent level this
year as well as for the near future, infrastructure needs for
East Asia are expected to total 1.2 trillion to 1.5 trillion
U.S. dollars over the next ten years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Adding South Asia together, investment in infrastructure is
likely to reach some 2 trillion U.S. dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
As these needs highly exceed the financial and managerial
capacity of the public sector, they can only be met if the private
sector's role is highly enhanced, Kohli stressed.
</P>
<P>
Now the share of private investment in East Asian
infrastructure is between 12 and 18 percent, with higher level of
private involvement anticipated, according to "Choices for
Efficient Provision of Infrastructure in East Asia", a report
co-edited by Kohli.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that East Asian economies, which enjoy some
of the highest savings rates in the world, develop their domestic
capital market for money-raising. Now only a quarter of the
financing for private infrastructure in East Asia comes from
domestic sources.
</P>
<P>
Total savings are running at 30-35 percent of gross domestic
product (GDP), and private savings at 25-30 percent in East Asia.
Moreover, a significant share of the savings is going into
financial assets.
</P>
<P>
So the issue is not a lack of domestic resources, and a more
mature domestic capital market will certainly help boost domestic
financing for private infrastructure, Kohli said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
