<HEADLINE> Indian Refinery Fire Toll Rises to 51 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the
devastating fire and explosions at an oil refinery complex in
India's Andhra Pradesh on Sunday has risen to 51 as 15 more bodies
were retrieved from the debris on Tuesday and today, Press Trust
of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The fire and blasts at the refinery complex, located in coastal
city Vishakhapatnam of Andhra Pradesh, were reportedly caused by a
leakage in the pipeline carrying liquefied petroleum gas from the
storage tanks to the port.
</P>
<P>
The spark that ignited following the leak carried the fire
along the pipeline to the storage tanks, causing a series of
explosions.
</P>
<P>
Amidst fears that more than 20 more bodies might still be
trapped underneath the rubble, rescue teams assisted by the Indian
naval forces continued to rummage through the debris using special
cranes and tippers, the PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Six buildings including the administrative block of the
refinery were razed to the ground under the impact of the massive
fire and explosions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
