<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asia Sees Fastest Growth in Export: WB Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- South Asia is witnessing
the world's fastest growth in exports in the period leading up to
2020, according to a World Bank report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The report, "South Asia's Integration into the World Economy",
said that the region is poised to be a major force in the global
trading system in the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Exports of the region have responded to new opportunities,
regional economies are opening up, direct investment inflows are
increasing, it said. Average nominal protection rates are now
around 20 to 25 percent, half of what they were five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Real exports grew at 11 percent a year in the 1990s, faster
than in any other region except East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the faster integration of the region into
the global economy holds the promise of higher growth rates and
the large-scale eradication of poverty.
</P>
<P>
But this will depend on whether South Asian countries can
continue to enact broad-based reforms, improve governance, and
further liberalize trade, it said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, John Williamson, World Bank Chief
Economist for South Asia Region, said the study also makes it
clear that South Asia still has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, South Asia continues to have the
highest tariffs in the world and more quantitative restrictions on
trade than most other regions.
</P>
<P>
Per capita exports are five times lower than in other
developing countries, and South Asia's share in world trade is
just 1 percent, compared with 4 percent for China. Intra-regional
trade is still minuscule, accounting for 4 percent of total trade,
it said.
</P>
<P>
South Asia remains the region with the highest incidence of
poverty and the largest absolute numbers of poor, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
