<HEADLINE> Malawian President Accused of Undermining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakilj
Muluzi has been accused of undermining the country's judiciary
independence after his calling on the former ruling Malawi
Congress Party (MCP) to apologize for a 1983 murder of four
politicians.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally Tuesday at Nkhata-bay in northern Malawi,
Muluzi said the people who allegedly killed the four men are
still within the MCP, Zambia's leading independent newspaper, The
Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a sharp response, Malawi lawyers described the president's
statement as "unfo"tunate" and said it undermines the
independence of Malawi's judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The legal practitigners said that all thE suspects in the
murder trial have been cleared of the allegations against them in
the high eourt and the supreme court.
</P>
<P>
Thrde former ministers, Aaron Gadama, ick Matenhe, Twaibu
Safgala, and legislator David Chiwanga were murdered 14 years ago
in southern Malawi during the MCP's rule under ex-President
Kamuzu Banda, who served his tenure of office during 1966-1994.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely believed in the country that the four
popular politicians died in a car accident until a commission of
enquiry set up by Muluzi, who succeeded Banda as president
following Malawi's first multi-party elections in 1994, found out
t`at the men were deliberately murdered.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the commission implicated that Banda, his
confidante Ceciia Kadzamira, his right-hand man John Tembo and
three senior police officers are involved in the killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
