<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Housing Problem Turns into Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese housing problem
has turned into a crisis that transcended low income groups
to hit middle income workers, according to a latest report by a
leading commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the Beirut-based Fransabank, one of the
leading commercial banks here, said that the middle income
workers make up 55 percent of Lebanon's labor force. Low income
groups live on 500 U.S. dollars or less a month while middle
income workers live on 500 to 2,000 dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
The report said that on the other hand, 60,000 to 100,000
housing units with 11 million to 15 million square meters
lay empty because developers overestimated the purchasing power
of the public who do not have access to long-term loans.
</P>
<P>
It called on the government to develop a secondary mortgage
market to solve the housing crisis and keep up with neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The primary mortgage market in Lebanon comprises 300 million
to 400 million dollars of extended and available loans. These
loans are provided by the state-owned housing bank and other six
private banks that extend 10-year loans at 11 to 13 percent
interest, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, it said that the amount of available loans does not
cover more than 7 percent of the 5.5 million to 7 million dollars
market value of the empty apartments. The loans are not long
enough and remain relatively expensive.
</P>
<P>
The report said a secondary mortgage market, which will provide
more liquidity and bring down mortgage prices, has a good chance
of succeeding in Lebanon because the country has a developed and
deregulated capital market and interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
