<HEADLINE> Diana's Car Could Be Blocked by Another Car: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Mercedes S280 sedan in
which Princess Diana and three others were travelling could have
been blocked by a Fiat car before the accident crash took place in
the mid-night between August 30 and 31, said police today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French investigators will have their first interview
Friday with Trevor Rees-Jones, the bodyguard of Diana, who is the
only survivor in the crash.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the ``meticulous'' examination of some glass
debris found near the Mercedes, which were apparently from a red
rear auto light, led them conclude the hypothesis of a possible
collision between the Mercedes and a Fiat car.
</P>
<P>
Two investigation judges, Marie-Christine Devidal and Herve
Stephan, will interview Rees-Jones, who has regained ``perfect
consciousness'' and can now communicate, reported Agence
France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones, 29, is suffering from light brain contusion, serious
facial injury and pulmonary contusion.
</P>
<P>
His testimony will be key to solve two questions: At what speed
was Henri Paul, the driver, who was also killed, driving the car?
Was there a car which tried to block the Mercedes when the accident
took place in the Alma tunnel in downtown Paris? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
