<HEADLINE> Large Enterprises to Lead China's Economy: Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Executives from 15
key state-owned firms in China shared the view that large
enterprises in the country should play a leading role in
China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The executives, all delegates to the Party congress now in
session here in Beijing, warmly responded to what Jiang Zemin said
in his report to the congress: "By using capital as the bonds and
relying on the market forces, we shall establish highly
competitive large enterprise groups with trans-regional,
inter-trade, cross-ownership and trans-national operations".
</P>
<P>
Enterprise groups play a key role in the entire national
economy. The 120 pilot enterprise groups which the government has
selected to carry out reforms, for instance, account for one
fourth of the entire state-sector of the economy, despite that
they only account for one per thousand in number, they noted.
</P>
<P>
"Large state-owned enterprises almost dominate the nation's key
industries," said Wang Guoxing, vice chairman of the board of
directors of the Handan Iron and Steel Group.
</P>
<P>
For instance, six power suppliers produce more than 50 percent
of the country's total power output for north China, northeast
China, east China, central China and northwest China, they said.
</P>
<P>
Eight iron and steel groups in the country turn out 40
percent of the total steel output, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
"Once large enterprises have been revitalized, the state sector
and even the entire national economy will be of
great promise," said Zhang Guixing, general manager of the
Northeastern Electric Power Group.
</P>
<P>
Among the first 57 pilot groups, 32 of them have been listed on
the stock market. Thirty of them have issued A shares, and three
of them have issued B shares. Besides, ten groups have gone
public beyond the boundary.
</P>
<P>
Last April, the number of pilot groups rose to 120, speaking
for the confidence of the central government to deepen reforms in
state-owned sector.
</P>
<P>
So far, a number of enterprise groups featuring diversified
operations across various industries and simultaneous engagement
in science, technology, production and trade, have come into
being.
</P>
<P>
"But enterprise groups in China still have a long way to go to
make themselves competitors of their overseas counterparts," said
Zhang Ruiming, president of the Haier Group which is the country's
largest household electric appliances producer.
</P>
<P>
Among the first 57 pilot groups, the sales volume of the
largest was just 5.8 billion US dollars while the last of the 500
businesses listed by the US magazine "Fortune" reported a sales
volume of 8.9 billion US dollars, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, China's large businesses now face an acute challenge
as a large number of overseas giants have entered China, he said,
adding that it is highly necessary to foster and develop
large enterprises and enhance their competitiveness in
the world, an executive from Shanghai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
