<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA -- The Bangladeshi government and the insurgent southern
tribal leaders have reached greater understanding in their
on-going peace talks which entered the fourth day on Wednesday,
according to sources close to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the two sides were trying to narrow down their
differences further over the status of the trouble-torn Chittagong
Hill Tracts (CHT), where Buddhist tribal people have been seeking
for self-rule since the early 1970s. (Bangladesh-Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran is ready to cooperate with Russia and other
countries to combat all forms of terrorism, Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi was quoted on Wednesday's English daily Iran News as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who was replying to a message from his Russian
counterpart Yevgeny Primakov, said Iran has an all-embracing and
realistic anti-terrorism scheme involving international
cooperation. But he did not elaborate.
(Iran-Russia-Anti-Terrorism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New Party
Sakigake agreed Tuesday to demand that an official convicted of
taking bribes resign from his new cabinet post, local press
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The SDP and Sakigake, two non-cabinet allies of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), will ask the LDP to relieve Koko
Sato, the newly appointed director general of the Management and
Coordination Agency, of his cabinet post when the three parties'
secretaries convene for a meeting on Wednesday, SDP officials
said. (Japan-Politics) 
