<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increases Earthquake Monitoring in Three Gorges Dam Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- China is increasing its
earthquake monitoring in the Three Gorges Dam area as construction
work there picks up steam.
</P>
<P>
The State Seismological Bureau will spend 57 million yuan on a
system to guard against possible earthquakes in the area.
</P>
<P>
When it is completed in the year 2009, the dam will have a
1,045-sq. km. reservoir with a capacity of 39.3 billion cubic
meters of water.
</P>
<P>
Seismologists say that the giant project could cause
construction-induced quakes, and if there is any, it will not be
so serious, because of the region's geographic structure and
topography.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Chinese experts began research in this area
30 years ago when the ideas of the dam first came up and tests
were done to provide data before the project was officially
approved.
</P>
<P>
Of the 35,000 dams in the world, there was a two-per-thousand
rate of earthquakes caused by construction and 80 percent of the
quakes recorded measured less than magnitude five on the Richter
Scale.
</P>
<P>
But, the higher the dam is, the bigger the potential for
earthquakes in the reservoir. And because the Yangtze River at the
construction site will be dammed in December, the water level in
the reservoir will be higher.
</P>
<P>
The State Seismological Bureau will start to build the monitoring
system this month for the whole construction area. It will also
set up a monitoring center at the dam site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
