<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Economies Fuel Global Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries have
become a powerful growth engine of an increasingly integrated
global economy, according to two keynote speakers today at the
three-day World Economic Development Congress which opened here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech entitled "The New Economic Order in Asia:
Economic, demographic and Geopolitical Issues", George Shultz, the
former US secretary of state, said there are two worlds in the
demographic view.
</P>
<P>
"One is wealthy and getting old, and it is a world in decline,
like West Europe; the other is poor and young, and in places where
growth happens, like Asia," he told more than 1,000 participants
at the Sixth World Economic Development Congress, a forum for
public and private sectors to discuss economic issues facing the
world.
</P>
<P>
The aging of population has greatly reduced the working force
in the developed world, such as Japan and Germany, while in
developing economies, like China, Chili, Brazil and Indonesia, the
labor contingent is growing rapidly, according to Shultz.
</P>
<P>
"This implicates that where the growth is coming, where the
infrastructure is bound to be located," said Shultz. Since the end
of the Cold War, he stressed, the global economy has become
integrated and security turned out to be a less concern.
</P>
<P>
Another speaker on the same topic was John Naisbitt, author of
the bestseller "Megatrends Asia", who told the Congress that the
Asian economy is currently shifted from being Japan-dominated to
being China-driven.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1992, the Congress is held each year immediately
before annual meetings of the World Bank Group and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and in the same venue.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, a special administrative Region of China, is hosting
the congress' meeting as well as the annual meetings of the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund for the first
time. 
</P>
