<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 100 in South-Western Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Cholera continues to bite in
Nyanza Province, south-western Kenya, claiming more than 100
lives in the past two months, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it seems more deaths go unreported as they occur
deep in the rural areas, said Daily Nation, a major paper
published in the Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
Many eating houses and filthy markets in the affected areas
have been closed down by public health officials.
</P>
<P>
"This disease is getting out of hand," a nurse there was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
District hospitals in Homa Bay, Rachuonyo, Suba and Migori and
rural-based health centers around these areas now are teemed with
cholera victims, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However( Richard Muga, a provincial medical officer, said
enough drugs and personnel had been sent out to contain the
spread, which is fueled by lack of clean drinking water and poor
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
He also urged provincial leaders and the church to help
spearhead public health and sanitation awareness as a measure to
curb the spread. 
</P>
</TEXT>
