<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks in Bangladesh Reach Greater Understanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government and
the insurgent southern tribal leaders have reached greater
understanding in their on-going peace talks which entered the
fourth day today, according to sources close to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the two sides were trying to narrow down their
differences further over the status of the trouble-torn Chittagong
Hill Tracts (CHT), where Buddhist tribal people have been seeking
for self-rule since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the sixth round being initiated by the government
for a formula to restore durable peace in the troubled hill
tracts, centered on points such as the land management in the CHT
and the region's administrative affairs, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Whip and Chairman of the National Committee on the CHT
Hasnat Abdullah was leading the government delegation at the
talks, while insurgent leader Bodhiprio Larma was the chief
negotiator of the Parbatya Chattagram Jano Sanghati Samity
(PCJSS), the political wing of the armed rebels in the CHT.
</P>
<P>
The PCJSS leaders were said to have demanded the tribal
people's ownership of the land in the CHT, which is however now
mostly occupied by the Bengali settlers.
</P>
<P>
The tribal delegation also demanded full control of the
proposed administration of the three resource-rich hill districts,
bordering India and Burma, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the two sides also discussed in detail the
draft of a long-hoped for peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
So far no official briefing has being given about the
proceedings of the dialogue which began here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Observers said both sides will have to make concessions if
there is to be a final agreement on the CHT and that their efforts
appear to be heading towards that direction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
