<HEADLINE> New Dar Market to House 1,200 Petty Traders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Over 1,200 petty
traders in Dar es Salaam will be allocated space for business in
the city's newly built Makumbushuo Market.
</P>
<P>
While officially inaugurating the market Tuesday, Chairman of
the National Income Generation Program (NIGP) Board, Richard
Mariki said that a total of 200,000 near-by residents will get
their service from the market.
</P>
<P>
The market which has been built under the supervision of the
NIGP and the City Council is also housing 80 kiosks for petty
businessmen including food stalls.
</P>
<P>
There are also 350 plots for selling vegetables, fruits and
cereals including a plot for wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the multi-purpose shop is aimed at
providing premises for petty businessmen who have been prohibited
from selling their merchandise in the city center by the City
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The project is also aimed at eradicating poverty among the Dar
es Salaam dwellers and a means of providing self-employment for
the unemployed and retrenched, according to Mariki. 
</P>
</TEXT>
