<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Economy on Sound Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- China's economy recorded a
healthy growth last month, featuring a steady industrial
production, a faster expansion of investment in fixed assets, and
a stable domestic market, according to a report released today by
the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
In August, the enterprises above township-level generated an
added value of 162.1 billion yuan, up 10.9 percent from the same
month in real terms. The growth rate stood at 8.4 percent in the
state sector, up 1.3 percentage points over that of the first
seven months this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the collectively-owned sector scored an increase
of 8.4 percent, according to the SSB report.
</P>
<P>
China made an accumulative investment of 764.5 billion yuan in
fixed assets during the January-August period, up 10.8 percent
over the same period in 1996. However, this increase margin
represents a drop of 9.4 percentage from that in the same period
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The investment in capital construction totaled 438.5 billion
yuan, up 16.5 percent; that in technical renovation and upgrading
was 151.2 billion yuan, up 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Due to a slack market, the investment in the real estate sector
dropped by two percent, standing at 13.46 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the country's retail sales climbed to
210.4 billion yuan in August, up 11.8 percent over the same period
in 1996. The retail sales in urban areas amounted to 129.1 billion
yuan, up 12.6 percent; that in rural areas hit 81.3 billion yuan,
up 10.6 percent. These two increase margins were, respectively,
one and 1.4 percentage points lower than last July's.
</P>
<P>
During the January-August period, China's retail sales stood
at 1.7 trillion yuan, up 13.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Economy on Sound Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last month China increased its foreign trade volume to 27.1
billion US dollars-worth, up 7.3 percent from the same month in
1996. Exports amounted to 16 billion US dollars, up 15.3 percent;
and imports reached 11.1 billion US dollars, down 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The accumulative exports reached 112.4 billion US dollars in
the first eight months this year, up 24.1 percent over the same
period in 1996, while imports came to 86.9 billion US dollars, up
1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
China has maintained a sound financial operation since the
start of this year, with the state's financial surging by 27.3
percent during the January-August period.
</P>
<P>
Also, the country's financial expenditures shot up by 19.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
The deposits in China's financial institutions increased by
100.4 billion yuan last month, representing a year-on-year drop of
34.7 billion yuan. In the meantime, the country also extended 81.8
billion yuan in loans, 6.1 billion yuan less than that of the
corresponding period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In August, the country's retail price index rose by a mere 0.1
percent over the same month last year. The consumer price index
edged up by 1.9 percent, representing one of the lowest increases
in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index and the consumer price index registered
an increase of 1.4 per cent and 3.6 percent, respectively, during
the first eight months this year.
</P>
<P>
The SSB reported said that in order to achieve a more rational
economic structure, the restructuring of state-owned enterprises
should be accelerated, while the balance between supply and demand
should be further improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
