<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Opens Doors for Nuclear Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- In a significant policy
shift, India has decided to throw open its two nuclear power
reactors at Kakrapar in Gujarat for inspection by international
experts, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two reactors will be opened up in November for visits by
members of the Tokyo-based World Association of Nuclear Operators
(WANO).
</P>
<P>
This follows an earlier move by India's Nuclear Power
Corporation (NPC) to subject its new 500 mw reactor design to
review by safety experts of the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA) in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
These latest efforts in increased transparency are seen as
India's response to both western and local criticism that the
country is operating vintage reactor of unsafe design.
</P>
<P>
NPC managing director Yelleswarapu Sivaram Prasad described the
Indian move as "voluntary" and "a confidence-building measure".
</P>
<P>
He said WANO members were free to inspect the control and
safety features installed in the Kakrapar Power Station and watch
all the activities going on.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
