<HEADLINE> Seles Wins in Princess Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Former world number one Monica
Seles defeated Tamarine Tanasugarn of Thailand in straight sets,
securing her spot in the quarterfinal of the 450,000 U.S. dollars
Princess Cup women's tennis tournament here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The top-seeded Yugoslav-born American struck forth with an easy
win of 6-1, 6-4 over the Thai star after rains interrupted the
game for half a hour when Seles led 6-1 and 0-1.
</P>
<P>
As the match resumed, Tanasugarn who was born in Los Angeles,
fought back with short balls to 4-4 despite against strong winds.
</P>
<P>
As the 20-year-old Thai player was high in spirit, Seles broke
the ninth game in time and served out the competition in 65
minutes.
</P>
<P>
In other actions, Patty Schnyder of Switzerland and Henrieta
Nagyova of Slovakia became the first seeded players to fall on the
hard courts.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Schnyder bowed to qualifier Maria-Alejandra Vento
of Venezuela 4-6, 0-6, while ninth seed Nagyova went down 6-2,
4-6, 1-6 to Naoko Sawamatsu of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Qualifier Shinobu Asagoe of Japan who ranked 259th, pulled off
her biggest win by beating 30th-ranked American Chanda Rubin 6-4,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
However, the 21-year-old Japanese woman faced a tough task as
she would meet second-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shi-ting of Chinese Taipei downed Japan's Naoko Kijimuta
4-6, 6-3, 6-1, Japanese qualifier Mana Endo outclassed Cristina
Torrens-Valero of Spain 6-4, 7-5 and Miho Saeki scored two
identical score of 6-4 to eliminate fellow Japanese Haruka Inoue.
</P>
</TEXT>
