<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Californian Residents, Scientists Prepare For El Nino Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Although predictions
about EL Nino differ, the U.S. state of California is quite prepared
even if all the bad things predicted never occur.
</P>
<P>
What has captured the media and public is whether the current
phenomenon would produce the extreme weather effects similar to
those during the last big and disastrous El Nino event in 1982-83.
</P>
<P>
Expectations about the current El Nino are so high that the
federal government has decided to hold a high-level meeting in
October on what California needs to prepare for the El Nino winter.
</P>
<P>
However, unlike ordinary people who are worried about the El
Nino effects, excited scientists of the West Coast just view it as
an opportunity to study one of nature's least-understood
phenomenon, as they were largely unprepared for the 1982-83 El
Nino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Uphold Fight Against Graft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government will leave no stone unturned in the fight against
graft in the public service.
</P>
<P>
This was pledged by Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye at a
dinner hosted for him in Hamburg, Germany, last night, according
to a news dispatch from that German city.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said that the government in Tanzania will wage the war
on corruption with all means at its disposal, describing
corruption as evil and a hindrance to private sector investment
as private investors look for a strong, accountable and
transparent system of government.
</P>
<P>
He challenged genuine investors to judge Tanzania on the basis
of its recent performance in economic reform programs, saying
that besides the reforms the government is also keen to ensure
good governance and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye is in Hamburg at the head of a strong delegation to the
Tanzania Trade and Investment Conference to be held there.
</P>
<P>
While opening the one-day meeting Monday, Sumaye said the
national industrial policy adopted by the government to guide
investment outlays over the next 25 years, aims at establishing a
strong industrial base which still lacks capital and genuine
investors.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that the main ingredients of the policy include
a comprehensive realization of the role of the sector played in
the socio-economic transformation for self-sustaining growth and
development.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye further said that as the government is implementing
such policy reforms, it intends to create a macro-economic and
institutional framework that will motivate the private sector to
perform and act as a gloss to the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Hamburg conference is jointly organized by the Tanzanian
government and the Hamburg-based German-Africa Association.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to provide yet another impetus for
increased economic cooperation between Tanzania and Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
