<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Parliament Approves Tax Hike Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian parliament today
approved -- after intense bickering and some scuffling -- a tax
reform package that would dramatically raise value-added taxes
</P>
<P>
Under the new bill, which was submitted by the new cabinet on
Monday, Albania's value-added tax rate will shoot up to 22 percent
from the original 12 percent as of October 1.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bill also stipulates an over-the-board hike of
consumption taxes on alcohol, tobacco, foodstuff and petroleum
products. Consumption tax rate on tobacco will rise to 70 percent
and imported lubricants and oils, 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the higher taxes, as demanded by the
International Monetary Fund as a major prerequisite for the
provision of emergency funding, will inevitably drive prices up.
</P>
<P>
The move was designed to cut the country's mammoth deficit,
which earlier this year stood at 30 billion Lek (209.8 million
U.S. dollars), estimated at 40 percent of its gross national
product (GNP).
</P>
<P>
Huha Kahkonen, an IMF official, said on September 3 that the
IMF would approve emergency funding for Albania at the end of next
month if the package could be implemented in October.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Arben Malaj said the government will come up
with a set of measures to mitigate the adverse effects on those
with lower incomes.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 1.2 million of Albania's 3.2 million
population are now living below the poverty line and 300,000
people are unemployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
