<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Revamp Aviation Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government has
decided to revamp its ailing aviation industry so as to meet both
military and civilian needs.
</P>
<P>
The "Financial News" newspaper reported today that under a
special reorganization program, the cash-strapped aviation
industry will be restructured to have only half of the existing
300 enterprises through mergers or close-downs.
</P>
<P>
After the restructuring, the industry will have only four
giants -- Mig, Sukhoi, Topolevand and Ilyushin -- as its backbone
to produce whole planes, and 10 to 15 companies as its second tier
supplying instruments, engines and auxiliary products.
</P>
<P>
Russia is estimated to need some 6,500 new civilian planes
before the year 2015, which, if imported, will cost the country 99
billion U.S. dollars. But designing and building by Russians
themselves will be much cheaper, costing only 53 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the government will only provide minimum
financial support for the development of new aircraft, and by
early 1999 there will be no wholly state-owned aviation
enterprises. The government will only reserve its controlling
right in their ownership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
