<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Reform Law Enforcing Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will take steps to
reform the law enforcing agencies which have drawn severe
criticism from the business community, local press reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
A draft of the guidelines for reforms will be prepared in
consultation with all circles concerned, the reports quoted Home
Affairs Minister Rafiqul Islam Bu as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will bring about a perfection through continuous reforms
and changes," Islam Bu told businessmen at a discussion on law and
order and smuggling sponsored by the Federation of Bangladesh
Chamber of Commerce and Industry (FBCCI).
</P>
<P>
He said corruption in the police forces as well as in other
parts of the administration was the legacy of past mismanagement.
"It will take time to clean up the garbage."
</P>
<P>
The minister said a department had been set up in the police
forces to deal with the law and order situation in business and
industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that the FBCCI form agencies in the chambers
across the country to collect information on law-breaking cases,
and asked the chambers to report the information to the home
ministry for further action.
</P>
<P>
On improper preparation of charge sheets that allowed culprits
to obtain bails from the courts, he said a special agency to be
formed by lawyers and officials would look into such cases and
tougher action would be taken against police officers who are
proved to be responsible for such lapses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
