<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Ringgit Weakens further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's ringgit,
which has been in a continuous downward trend for the last few
days, took a fresh beating in early trade today, breaching the
3.00 ringgit level against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
On selling of ringgit for the greenback from offshore funds
following renewed concerns about the state of Thailand's economy,
the local currency was opened this morning at 3.0100/50 against
the U.S. dollar compared to 2.9900/30 at the close yesterday.
</P>
<P>
This was a new low of the ringgit since 1970 when it was once
traded at 3.0775 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit also weakened against other major currencies. It
fell to 1.9848/94 against the Singapore dollar from 1.9752/85 at
the close yesterday and to 4.8076/71 against the pound sterling
from 4.7607/84.
</P>
<P>
Against the deutschemark, the ringgit dropped to 1.7015/45 from
1.6908/34 and against the Japanese Yen, it weakened to 2.4876/38
from 2.4770/16.
</P>
<P>
The reported possible withdrawal of an International Monetary
Fund rescue package for Thailand was attributed to the weakening
of regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in Thailand is not over yet and will haunt the
region for a while, a dealer said, expecting the ringgit to stay
above the 3.00 ringgit level to the U.S. dollar for a while as
sentiment on the local unit is bearish.  
</P>
</TEXT>
