<HEADLINE> SDP, Sakigake Demand Convicted Bribetaker Quit Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Social Democratic Party
(SDP) and New Party Sakigake agreed Tuesday to demand that an
official convicted of taking bribes resign from his new cabinet
post, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The SDP and Sakigake, two non-cabinet allies of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), will ask the LDP to relieve Koko
Sato, the newly appointed director general of the Management and
Coordination Agency, of his cabinet post when the three parties'
secretaries convene for a meeting on Wednesday, SDP officials said.
</P>
<P>
Sato, a veteran politician convicted of taking bribes in the
1976 Lockheed scandal, was included in Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's new cabinet in a reshuffle last Thursday. He is the
first person convicted of bribery to join a cabinet in the postwar
period in Japan.
</P>
<P>
In a general meeting of SDP lawmakers from both chambers of the
Diet (parliament) on Tuesday, many criticized Sato for accepting
the cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
Some senior members of the SDP called on the party to abandon
its alliance with the LDP if Sato remained in his post.
</P>
<P>
SDP leader Takako Doi made clear in the meeting that she would
take a tough stance, saying, "This is an important case that may
affect democracy in Japan."
</P>
<P>
After the meeting of the Diet, the SDP decided at its executive
meeting that the party would demand the resignation of Sato and
boycott most meetings with the LDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
