<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Dead, 5,000 Homeless in Floods in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Floods caused by three days
of ceaseless torrential rains in several parts of Sri Lanka have
killed 13 people and rendered over 5,000 homeless, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Continuous rains, starting on Sunday night, have caused serious
floods and land slides in Avissawella, 50 kilometers east of
Colombo, and Ratnapura District.
</P>
<P>
On Monday alone, five people were confirmed killed and more
than 3,000 people were rendered homeless in the floods in
Avissawella, one of the worst affected areas. Many others were
reported missing.
</P>
<P>
Other deaths were reported in Habaraduwa, Dehiowita in the
southern area and Haputale and Badulla in central mountain areas
which were also badly hit by the rains.
</P>
<P>
The floods destroyed several parts of the main roads. Train
services were also disrupted due to the rains.
</P>
<P>
In Colombo, capital of this Indian Ocean island nation, the
waters of the Kelani River have risen to the warning level. Floods
are feared to wash out the low lying areas of the city today if
the rain continues.
</P>
<P>
The local government has to place those homeless in schools,
temples and community centers.
</P>
<P>
So far the estimated damage caused by the floods was about 25
million rupees (420,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan Meteorological Department has attributed the
disastrous rains to the weak southwest monsoon winds, which were
conducive to thundershowers. The department has forecast that the
rain will continue for another two days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah, Stocks Fall on Regional Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah and
local stock prices weakened on Tuesday despite the government's
announcement on project rescheduling, dealers and brokers here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah weakened to a low of 2,955 against the U.S. dollar
from an opening of 2,930/2,938 before settling at 2,948/2,952 at
Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
Sustained regional weakness and concern that the riot in
Ujungpandang, capital of Indonesia's South Selawesi province,
might spread kept the rupiah under pressure and caused relatively
heavy bidding on the U.S. dollar, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jakarta Stock Exchange composite index slipped
2.89 percent to 534.83 points at Tuesday's close despite a 0.5
percent gain at the opening in anticipation of the retrenchment
program.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the government's retrenchment program should have
sent a positive signal to the market, but it failed to lift the
market.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad announced before a
parliamentary plenary session Tuesday that the government would
postpone or review 35.6 billion U.S. dollars worth of government
and state-related projects as part of the drastic measures to cope
with the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the central bank has reduced its bank Indonesia
certificate (SBI) for one month and three month periods by seven
percent in order to ease the tight monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 25 percent since January this year following offshore
speculative attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies
to hedge their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
