<HEADLINE> IMF Diagnoses Southeast Asia Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Real currency appreciation
and a fragile financial sector, rather than fiscal imbalances, are
said to have ignited the Southeast Asia's currency crisis, which
sank currencies of these emerging economies to record lows,
according to a report released by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) here today.
</P>
<P>
The World Economic Outlook, published a week before this year's
 Annual Meetings of the World Bank and the IMF, picked up the
recent speculative attacks on the currencies of some emerging
market economies as a global issue and tried to find the factors
behind.
</P>
<P>
The currency turmoil hit Thailand the hardest, to which the IMF
later provided a rescue package worth of 17.2 billion U.S. dollars
to bail the economy out. The Thai baht crunch soon spilled over
to other currencies in the region -- the Philippine peso,
Malaysian ringgit, Indonesian rupiah, and even the robust
Singaporean dollar all were depreciated.
</P>
<P>
"The trigger point is likely to depend upon the circumstances
and characteristics of the economy in question, including its
exchange rate policy, its degree of openness, its savings and
investment behavior, the nature of the capital flows financing its
balance of payment deficit, and the health of its financial
system," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Before the speculators mounted attacks on its currency,
Thailand had recently experienced appreciation of both real and
nominal effective exchange rate, which, coupled with a widening
current account deficit, may have increased the perceived risk of
a crisis, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In fast-growing economies, rapid capital inflows in recent
years have built up inflationary pressures and the real exchange
rates tend to appreciate through higher domestic inflation, the
report analyzed.
</P>
<P>
"As signs of overheating and of the tension between the
authorities' desire, on the one hand, to contain inflation and, on
the other, to maintain a stable exchange rate become increasingly
apparent, investors are likely to begin to doubt whether the
situation is sustainable," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the Thailand case, sluggish exports had recently slowed down
its economic growth, raising doubts about the authority's
continued willingness to support the exchange rate by maintaining
high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"A turnaround in market sentiment can then bring about a sudden
reversal in capital flows and an external financing crunch that
could result in significant losses in international reserves or a
large adjustment in the exchange rate," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Weaknesses in the banking sector, such as heavy reliance on
short-term borrowing, excessive lending to property-related
projects, poor supervision and inadequate prudential regulations,
tend to make developing economies vulnerable to a sudden reversal
of capital inflows, according to the report. Thailand fell into
the category.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that the large external current account
deficit in Thailand, around ten percent of its GDP growth in 1996,
is by no means a determinative factor to stir up the currency
turbulence. "Neither theory nor experience suggests some
definitive threshold level for the current account deficit that
may be expected to trigger an external crisis."
</P>
<P>
It highlighted the significant spillover effects of crisis in
one country on other countries in the region, which share common
risk factors, such as real currency appreciation against a rigid
exchange rate system, large external debts and too much domestic
credit to booming property and construction sectors.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent currency upheavals, the report said that the
overall outlook for capital flows to developing countries remains
broadly positive.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the trigger point for such reversals is difficult
to predict, the report concluded that the best defense is to
pursue policies that address the emergence of imbalances before
they get out of control.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suggested that developing economies establish a set of
core regulatory standards for stronger banking supervision and
learn to manage volatility of cross-border capital flows.
</P>
</TEXT>
