<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Boost Investment in Railroad Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government will
invest 35 trillion lire (20 million U.S. dollars) in modernizing
the country's railway network over the next 10 years, Transport
Minister Claudio Burlando said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a hearing of the Senate Public Works Committee,
Burlando said the money would be used to maintain the existing
network and introduce new technology and equipment. About 17.5
trillion lire of the total amount is expected to go toward a
high-speed rail project, while the other half will be spent in
improving the current rail system.
</P>
<P>
Burlando stressed the need for railroad reformation and
regarded it as an urgent task facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The State Railway came under fire in early August when a series
of accidents caused tens of thousands of passengers to be stranded
in Rome on the biggest travel weekend of the year. The crisis was
seen as the latest sign of an aging, out-of-date system.
</P>
<P>
Burlando said 40 percent of the money will be ready in 1998.
He expressed his optimism over the investment plan saying that the
State Railway and National Treasury officials have reached a
consensus on the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
