<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Growth of Developing Countries to Remain Buoyant: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The growth of the real
gross domestic product (GDP) in developing countries is expected
to remain buoyant at slightly over six percent in 1997 and
similar growth is projected for 1998, the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of the "World Economic Outlook" released
this morning said in most developing countries, low or declining
inflation and generally prudent fiscal policies suggest that
threats to growth arising from policy imbalances have been
significantly reduced, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out, in a number of cases, large
external imbalances and fragile banking systems have emerged and
affected investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
But such short-term difficulties should not significantly
affect the generally positive long-term prospects of these
countries provided macroeconomic stability is not jeopardized and
the necessary reforms are implemented without undue delay.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, several countries have recently experienced financial
market pressures linked to concerns about large external deficits.
</P>
<P>
Growth in some Southeast Asian countries is likely to slow
significantly in the short run following the recent financial
crisis in the region but should subsequently return to its quite
strong longer-term trend, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The soft landing of China's economy has succeeded in
alleviating inflationary pressures: consumer price inflation is
expected to moderate to 4.5 percent in 1997, a striking contrast
with the 22 percent inflation rate registered in 1994. At the same
time, growth has been maintained at over nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Solid growth is also projected to continue in India. The reform
process under way in the country since 1992 has already produced
notable results, raising annual growth to about seven percent
since 1994 compared with about five percent through the 1980s and
early 1990s, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries in the Middle East and Europe region have
witnessed significant improvements in economic performance in
recent years and average growth is expected to continue in the
four to five percent range in 1997-98 despite a slight decline in
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
For Africa, the overall growth estimate for 1997 has been
revised down to 3.75 percent compared with 4.5 percent in the May
edition of "World Economic Outlook".
</P>
<P>
The downward revision appears disappointing following the
relatively encouraging outcome for 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, this result is strongly influenced by developments
such as drought in Morocco, and civil war and political turmoil in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo and the Republic of the
Congo.
</P>
<P>
Overall, while the fragility of Africa's recovery is
highlighted by recent setbacks and political uncertainties, there
are also a significant number of relatively successful economies
that illustrate the region's potential for reversing the long-run
decline in living standards during much of the past quarter
century.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, growth in Africa is projected to recover to about 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
In the Western Hemisphere, both Argentina and Mexico have
continued to recover following the 1995 crisis, and growth is
expected to remain fairly strong during the period ahead.
</P>
<P>
In Brazil, inflation has continued to abate and is expected to
fall below eight percent in 1997, but the external deficit has
been rising.
</P>
<P>
In Chile, growth and inflation have slowed somewhat as a result
of measures to address the risk of overheating; healthy
fundamentals point to continued medium-term growth in the range of
six to seven percent.
</P>
<P>
While Chile's economy remains the strongest among the
developing countries of the Western Hemisphere, there are
encouraging signs that improved macroeconomic discipline and
intensified structural reform efforts are improving the growth
outlook for other countries in the region, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
