<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF on Prospects for Growth in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- South Asia, the second
fastest growing region after East Asia in the world for the past
decade, will maintain its growth momentum provided that
comprehensive economic reforms are continued, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of "World Economic Outlook" released here
this morning said that projected growth for India, the giant in
the subcontinent, remains at 6.5 percent, well above the average
of five percent achieved in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Following the reform program that India initiated in 1991-92,
growth in real Gross Domestic Product recovered, and then
accelerated, registering about 7 percent a year in the period
1994-96," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been some recent deceleration in economic activity,
concentrated in industrial production and stemming for weakness in
investment and export. Nevertheless, with agricultural performance
benefiting from a favorable monsoon, projected growth for 1997
remains at 6.5 percent," the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is expected to remain moderate, while the external
position should continue to be comfortable with a current account
deficit of less than two percent of GDP and private capital inflows
continuing to be strong, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"A more comprehensive and deep-rooted second wave of reform
measures" remain to be implemented to sustain and improve India's
growth performance of the recent past and to reach its full
potential, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Achieving higher growth in India over the medium term will
depend on mutually reinforcing fiscal measures and structural
reforms," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Turning to Pakistan, the report said, growth projection has
been revised downward to three percent against the five percent
registered for both 1995 and 1996, in the wake of last year's
balance of payments crisis and subsequent adjustment measures.
</P>
<P>
Facing widening macroeconomic imbalances and a threat of
foreign exchange crisis in the latter half of 1996, the Pakistani
authorities adopted a wide-ranging policy package to strengthen
macroeconomic policies and implement structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The structural components of the policy package were
strengthened substantially in the first half of 1997 in such areas
as tariff reform, tax reform, and financial sector restructuring.
These efforts hold promise of a recovery of GDP growth to the five to
six percent range, as well as of a more stable macroeconomic
environment, said the report.
</P>
<P>
This prospect is contingent, however, upon the sustained
implementation of stabilization and structural policies, it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
In Sri Lanka, the macroeconomic situation has improved since
mid-1996, with the end of the drought and the power shortages, the
report said, adding that growth, which had slowed to under four
percent in 1996, is expected to recover to six percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Persistently large fiscal deficits are at the heart of many of
Sri Lanka's economic problems including the lack of durable
inflation control and relatively modest growth, it noted.
</P>
<P>
After two consecutive years of fiscal deficits in excess of 10
percent of GDP, the deficit narrowed slightly to 9.5 percent in
1996, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 budget, which aims to reduce the deficit by two
percentage points of GDP, is a good start to the medium-term
fiscal consolidation but further fiscal adjustment is necessary,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to Bangladesh, the report said, although economic
growth rose to nearly five percent during the first half of the
1990s, poverty remained pervasive.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate progress in removing deep-seated structural
rigidities in the economy, including a large public sector and a
weak and undercapitalized banking system, made it difficult to
attain a more rapid rate of growth and poverty reduction, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
