<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Predicts Robust Growth in Transition Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Many of the transition
countries have achieved robust growth in their economy, according
to a report issued here today by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
The robust growth trends in these countries can be attributed
to the success of a growing number of economies in establishing
and maintaining macroeconomic stability and in pursuing
outward-oriented, market-based reforms, said the latest edition of
 "World Economic Outlook".
</P>
<P>
There are increasingly encouraging signs that in some
transition countries including Poland, the Baltic countries, the
Czech Republic, Slovak Republic, Hungary and Slovenia, which have
pursued comprehensive stabilization and reform policies.
</P>
<P>
The report said that these countries are experiencing
relatively solid growth, moderate inflation, and good progress in
their reintegration into the world economic and financial system.
</P>
<P>
In the countries in transition as a group, output in 1997 is
now projected to increase by 1.5 to two percent, the first
significant positive growth rate in eight years.
</P>
<P>
The countries more advanced in transition have generally
continued to make progress in reducing inflation, while growth has
 picked up in a number of countries, including Hungary. In Poland,
 inflation on a 12-month basis has fallen below 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
In other countries less advanced in transition, Russia and most
 other countries of the former Soviet Union have made substantial
progress in bringing down inflation.
</P>
<P>
The report said that many challenges remain to be addressed to
safeguard and further extend the progress that has been achieved
in many of the less advanced transition countries. There remains a
 need to establish the institutions of a market economy, which are
 still rudimentary.
</P>
<P>
In addition to fiscal and structural policy requirements, the
transition countries generally face substantial challenges in the
area of monetary policy, the report added. Further progress is
also needed to put in place the framework of instruments and
institutions through which monetary policy can be operated in a
market economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
