<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: Southeast Asian Economy to Return to Fast Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Several Southeastern Asian
countries, which have been plagued by a recent currency turmoil,
are likely to experience a slowdown in the months ahead, but
should gradually return to strong economic performance, the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) said today.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of "World Economic Outlook" released here
this morning said, "In Asia, despite the region's impressive
growth performance in recent years, several countries have
recently experienced financial market pressures linked to concerns
about large external deficits."
</P>
<P>
The pressures have been most acute in Thailand, where
fragilities in the banking system contributed to market concerns,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
After a series of attacks on the baht, a more flexible exchange
rate regime was introduced in early July and there has since been
a depreciation of over 30 percent against the U.S. dollar, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Provided adequate measures are adopted to strengthen the
financial sector and the balance of payments, confidence should be
restored relatively quickly, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in Thailand is likely to slow significantly in the
short run but should subsequently return to its quite strong
longer-term trend," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Projected growth for the country has been downgraded by 3.5-4
percentage points to 2.5 percent, reflecting both the effects of
the crisis itself and the adjustment measures put in place.
</P>
<P>
Spillovers were felt by several countries in the region,
especially the Philippines, Indonesia and Malaysia, the report
said, downgrading growth projections for all of these countries by
0.5 to 1.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Asia is projected to remain the fastest growing region in the
developing world, and even with the downward revisions to growth
projections for 1997 and 1998 owing mainly to the currency
turmoil, its expansion this year, by 7.5 percent, will still
significantly exceed average growth in the 1980s and early 1990s,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also stressed that as of early September, broader
spillover effects of the crisis on other emerging market economies
in Asia remained fairly limited.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore dollar weakened moderately in July and August,
the Hong Kong dollar also briefly came under pressure in
mid-August. Equity prices generally weakened across the region in
July and August.
</P>
<P>
The report noted, "Overall, there are reasons to believe that
the currency turbulence will eventually wane without greatly
damaging the region's long-term prospects." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Expects Turnaround in Thai Economy Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) today expressed his confidence
in a gradual improvement in Thailand's economy next year as
efforts to tackle the currency crisis have begun to take effect.
</P>
<P>
Michael Mussa, IMF economic counselor and director of the
Research Department, told a press conference here this morning
that although it is difficult to tell exactly when the market
pressure will come down, he expects the Thai economy to improve in
the next six months to one year.
</P>
<P>
While there is still an adjustment process in both the market
and financial policy, rescue measures "are indeed in place", he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Within the coming year, you can see a turnaround in the
economy," Mussa predicted.
</P>
<P>
The market has overdone in the crisis for the past two months,
leading to a sharp depreciation of the Thai currency, and the key
problem now is to restore market confidence, he said.
</P>
<P>
The international financial community has sent a clear signal
to the market that the overreaction should be corrected, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
