<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF on European Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The advent of European
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) scheduled for the beginning of
1999 will constitute a major change in the international monetary
system, according to a report issued here today by International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of "World Economic Outlook", a report on
world economic and financial surveys, said that involving the
replacement of the national currencies of a number of highly
developed economies of substantial size by a single common
currency, EMU will in fact have no parallel in history.
</P>
<P>
The achievement of EMU will reflect over 40 years of progress
in strengthening economic, monetary, and political ties within
Europe.
</P>
<P>
It said that the EU countries have made considerable progress
in macroeconomic convergence.
</P>
<P>
The inflation in the EU is now lower than at any other time in
the last 35 years. For 1997, average consumer price inflation in
the EU as a whole is projected at 2 percent, less than half of
what it was when the treaty was agreed in 1991, with all EU
members, except Greece, expected to have inflation below 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Important improvements have also been made in the fiscal area.
The EU-wide general government deficit in 1997 is projected at
2.75 percent of GDP, some 3.5 percentage points lower than its
peak in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that the countries' efforts to improve
inflation and fiscal performance in recent years have not been
without short-term costs in terms of weaker activity.
</P>
<P>
But the costs of fiscal consolidation should not be
exaggerated, it said.
</P>
<P>
The faltering of Europe's recovery in 1995-96 also reflected
the impact on confidence of inadequacies in structural policies in
many countries -- notably the slow pace of labor market reforms,
but also limited progress in the reform of government spending
programs and the consequent overdependence on tax measures in
fiscal consolidation efforts.
</P>
<P>
On the unavoidable uncertainty following the introduction of
the new currency and the possibility of large movements in
exchange rates, the report said that they may lead to greater
calls for international policy coordination between EMU and other
countries, particularly in dealing with any perceived misalignment
of exchange rates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Outlines Situation in Advanced Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Stronger growth in the
advanced economies may help the global economy in the future
decade, but these well-developed countries face different
problems, according to a report issued by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) today.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of "World Economic Outlook" said that the
global economy is enjoying the fourth episode of relatively rapid
growth since the early 1970s and the good tendency is backed by
stronger growth in the advanced economies.
</P>
<P>
The report took note of continued solid growth with low
inflation in the United States and Britain, strengthening recovery
in Canada and a broadening of recovery across continental Western
Europe. "Stronger growth during the period ahead in these
countries should help support global demand and activity," it
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out, the advanced countries have
different conditions for each own economic development and face
different situations.
</P>
<P>
The high degree of price stability remains an impressive
achievement shared by almost all of the advanced economies,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"In 1996, the rate of consumer price inflation averaged 2.5
percent, and only four countries experienced inflation above 5
percent; measured by GDP deflators, a broader measure of the price
level, average inflation was just 2 percent," it said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of output and employment, the picture in these
advanced countries is much more mixed as underscored by sharp
divergences in labor market performance in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas a number of economies including the United States,
Britain, and several of the smaller advanced economies are
operating at relatively high levels of resource use," the report
continued, "the three major continental European countries
(Germany, France and Italy) have suffered protracted economic
weakness that has been accompanied by a dramatic rise in
unemployment to post-war record levels."
</P>
<P>
Conditions for recovery in the advanced economies have
gradually improved, but few forecasters expect the upswing to make
more than a modest dent in unemployment. In Japan, the recovery
has also proven quite hesitant.
</P>
<P>
As to the unsatisfactory economic performance of Germany,
France and Italy, the report said, "The sources of (their)
weakness have been internal."
</P>
<P>
It attributed the following major four factors to the
sluggishness, such as lack of substantial fiscal consolidation,
lack of flexibility of labor markets, lack of consumer and
business confidence and lack of a justified monetary policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Forecasts 4.2 Pct World Economic Growth This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The global economy is
expected to grow by 4.2 percent this year and 4.3 percent in 1998,
 the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said today.
</P>
<P>
With the strongest pace in a decade, the world economy is
enjoying the fourth episode of relatively rapid growth since the
early 1970s, according to the latest edition of the IMF's "World
Economic Outlook" released here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation will remain subdued in the advanced
economies at about two percent, and decline further in the
developing countries and the countries in transition, the IMF
said.
</P>
<P>
Robust world trade expansion will contribute greatly to the
solid economic growth, with annual trade volume, goods and
services included, forecast to increase by 7.7 percent this year
and 6.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF described the high degree of price stability as an
impressive achievement shared by almost all of the advanced
economies, predicting an average of 2.2 percent consumer price
inflation along with an average of three percent economic growth
for them.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) in
Europe, the IMF believes that the establishment of EMU will be a
milestone in the 40-year-long quest to strengthen economic and
monetary integration in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"For Europe, it is to be hoped that EMU will herald a new era
of stronger economic growth," the IMF said, noting that a common
currency shared by a majority of EU member countries, and
potentially by all of them, will lower transaction costs and
generally promote economic integration, generating long-term
efficiency gains.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF also called for close attention to be placed
on uncertainties about the EMU, suggesting that investor sentiment
 may change if the feasibility of the timetable is perceived to be
 threatened, which will probably lead to unwelcome upward pressure
 on currencies of some countries and weaker economic confidence.
</P>
<P>
The report expected real Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth in
 the developing countries to remain relatively buoyant at around
6.2 percent in 1997, compared to 6.5 percent last year, and their
average consumer price inflation will drop from 13.2 percent last
year to ten percent this year.
</P>
<P>
"While the rapid expansion in the Asian region is projected to
moderate somewhat further, many countries in other regions that
saw a marked strengthening of activity in 1996 are expected to
sustain this improvement in the period ahead," the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the IMF again cautioned that the integration of developing
countries into world financial market "poses significant
challenges".
</P>
<P>
While capital inflows can substantially enhance countries'
growth performance, "experience shows that persistently large
deficits are likely sooner or later to result in highly disruptive
 changes in market sentiment," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid possible damages by such changes, the IMF
underlined "the frequent need to strengthen fiscal policy" and
"the need for prudential rules that limit the banking system's
exposure to domestic loan problems and to foreign exchange and
liquidity risks" as well as the need for "a gradual introduction
of capital account convertibility".
</P>
<P>
On economic prospects of transition countries, the IMF took
notice of "increasingly encouraging signs that the process of
transition is working".
</P>
<P>
Those countries which have pursued comprehensive stabilization
and reform policies are experiencing relatively solid growth,
moderate inflation, and good progress in their reintegration into
the world economic and financial system, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in the transition countries is expected to
reach an average of 1.8 percent this year, compared to 0.1 percent
 last year, and their average consumer price inflation will go
down to 32 percent this year from 40 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"Despite slow progress in some cases, 1997 seems likely to be
the first year for the transition countries overall to register
positive growth," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that many challenges remain to be addressed for
those transition countries, including the needs to establish the
institutions of a market economy, restructure former state-owned
enterprises, improve financial system and policy-making, and
strengthen macroeconomic stability.
</P>
<P>
While macroeconomic stability, trade liberalization, and the
creation of the basic institutional framework of a market economy
are essential for stronger growth, broader-based reforms are
necessary to sustain and enhance countries' longer-run growth
performance and ensure that the benefits of reform are more widely
 shared, the IMF said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
