<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: HKSAR, Mainland Economic Integration Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Economic integration
between the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China
 and the Chinese mainland has advanced steadily since the
initiation of China's reform process in 1978, according to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The "World Economic Outlook" released by the IMF here today
said that HKSAR's economic performance remains impressive as its
handover to China has proceeded smoothly, and the links between
the two economies in production, investment, trade and financial
flows have been on the increase.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that HKSAR's GDP will have a 5.3 percent
growth for 1997 and a 5.0 percent growth for 1998, while consumer
price inflation will be 7.1 percent and 6.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
It said that the increased economic integration has coincided
with dramatic structural changes of Hong Kong's economy from one
that was based on manufacturing to one dominated by the services
sector.
</P>
<P>
Investment from Hong Kong accounts for two-thirds of foreign
direct investment in the mainland since 1979 and provides
employment for an estimated 4 to 5 million workers in southern
provinces. As production facilities have been relocated to the
mainland, cyclical fluctuations in Hong Kong's GDP and the
mainland's industrial production have become increasingly
correlated.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade flows have also expanded steadily. Around 55
percent of Hong Kong's re-exports are originated in the mainland
and about 35 percent are destined to the mainland. One-fourth of
Hong Kong's domestic exports in recent years have gone to the
mainland, although only six percent of retained imports have
originated in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
While banking and financial links have developed, the degree of
financial integration remains limited, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Corruption Remains Arduous Task: Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the 15th
Communist Party National Congress shared the view that China still
faces the arduous task of fighting corruption and should continue
it perseveringly.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Jiang Zemin's call for never allowing
corruptionists to hide themselves within the Party drew a burst of
applause from all participants at the opening session of the Party
congress reflected the heartfelt wishes of the whole Party and the
people across the country, said a delegate.
</P>
<P>
Li Jinhua, member of the Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection (CCDI), said progress has been made in the fight
against corruption since the 14th National Party Congress held in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Discipline inspection departments at various levels in the
country have tracked down a number of key cases and took
disciplinary actions against more than 20,000 officials at the
county (section) levels and 1,600 officials at the prefecture
(department) level.
</P>
<P>
Li Moran, a delegate in the capacity of a film star, said that
at first he worried about the case of Chen Xitong, former
secretary of the Beijing Municipal Party Committee, fearing that
it would end up with nothing definite.
</P>
<P>
"I was delighted with CCDI's decision on Chen Xitong, which
will help to improve the prestige of the Party," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Siqing, president of the Supreme People's Procuratorate,
said the Party has found an effective way to curb corruption,
which has a unified leadership with support from discipline
inspection departments and the broad masses.
</P>
<P>
Hou Zongbin, CCDI deputy secretary, said the next five years
will be a period of deepening reform and accelerated economic
development as well as a crucial period of fight against
corruption.
</P>
<P>
The key to fighting corruption is to speed up economic and
political restructuring and root out the hotbed which breeds
corruption, he added.
</P>
<P>
Guo Fenglian, Party secretary of Dazhai Village in north
China's Shanxi Province, said: "We have no reason to practice
extravagance and waste as 50 million rural population have not got
rid of poverty and many urban dwellers are still leading a poor
life. Graft by a tiny number of communists has damaged the
prestige of the Party."
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, a delegate from Beijing, said: "We should
strengthen the fight against corruption, tighten supervision,
deepen the reform and pay attention to both present and future
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
