<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Outlines U.N. Reform Emphasis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The reform of the United
Nations should emphasize the structural rationalization of the
world body rather than just budget-cuts, said a Russian official.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing today, Foreign Ministry official Sergey
Ordzonikidze said that eliminating the overlapped
U.N. institutions will make the world body more structurally
rational and responsive to the practical needs of its member
states.
</P>
<P>
He said that at the upcoming U.N. General Assembly meeting, the
Russian delegation will work for the establishment of a new world
order based on consolidated collective security and mutually
beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the reform of the U.N. Security Council, the official said
Russia believes that the council's membership could be expanded to
20, including Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that in enforcing violent and mandatory
operations, the U.N. should strictly observe the clearly-defined
provisions of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that Russia will cooperate with the U.N. in solving
the conflicts in the members of the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
