<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Unveils New Space Instrument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Space Agency
(CSA) unveiled here today a new space instrument that is expected
to put Canada squarely at the front of global ozone research.
</P>
<P>
The sensor, named Optical Spectrograph and Infrared Imager
System (OSIRIS), will provide ozone data of unparalled detail to
the global scientific community, CSA said.
</P>
<P>
While previous ozone studies have examined the extent and
progress of the ozone problem, the OSIRIS study will be the first
to measure the concentration of ozone-depleting pollutants
themselves.
</P>
<P>
With this knowledge, scientists will be able to positively
identify human activities that contribute to the problem.
</P>
<P>
The unveiling is part of the celebrations marking the 10th
anniversary of the signing of the Montreal Protocol, which is
being formally celebrated in Montreal today.
</P>
<P>
CSA said that OSIRIS will be one of two major instruments
onboard the Swedish ODIN satellite, scheduled to launch in the
fall of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
