<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Port to Become International Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the Haicang
section at Xiamen Port in Fujian Province, on the western shores
of the Taiwan Straits, has been in progress since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the project is to expand both the area and capacity
of the east China port, and eventually transform it into an
international shipping center.
</P>
<P>
The Xiamen city government plans to promote local economic
development by accelerating construction of the port area,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Deep-water berths in the Dongdu section of the port currently
have an annual handling capacity of 14 million tons. The
capacity is expected to raise to 35 million tons upon completion
of the ongoing construction.
</P>
<P>
The Haicang Section, with a coast line of 13 km, will include
49 deep-water berths with each having a handling capacity of at
least 10,000 tons. Estimates call for the section's total annual
capacity to hit 90 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The two sections will raise the annual handling capacity of
Xiamen Port to over 100 million tons, a level which port
authorities regard as a key factor which will enable the port to
become an international shipping center in future.
</P>
<P>
Four berths for oil, coal, container and sundry goods were
completed in the Haicang Section in the first two years of
construction.
</P>
<P>
In addition, an expansion project will enable the Xiamen
Shipyard to build vessels rated at 10,000 dwt and to repair vessel
rated at 20,000 dwt.
</P>
<P>
Additional berths, as well as various other port facilities and
infrastructures such as roads, railways and bridges are scheduled
for construction in the coming years. Local sources report that
foreign investors have shown increasing interest in participating
in related projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
