<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Expected in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The economy in Latin
American and Caribbean countries as a whole is expected to grow
4.5 percent this year, the Economic Commission for Latin America
and the Caribbean (CEPAL) reported.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the region posted a 3.5 percent gross domestic
product (GDP) growth.
</P>
<P>
CEPAL said that foreign capital flowing into the region is
expected to reach 70 billion U.S. dollars this year, as against
57 billion and 63 billion dollars in 1994 and 1996 respectively.
</P>
<P>
CEPAL forecast that the region's current account deficit will
rise to 56 billion dollars in 1997, 24 billion dollars higher than
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt of the region will total 650 billion dollars in
1997, up five percent over last year's.
</P>
<P>
Regional exports are also expected to increase 11 percent to
277 billion dollars, while imports will grow 20 percent to 290
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
