<HEADLINE> Driver Believes Mechanical Failure Causes Senna Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Ferrari driver Michele
Alboreto claimed Tuesday at an Italian court that a mechanical
failure caused Ayrton Senna's fatal crash during the 1994 San
Marino Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time Alboreto appeared at the trial which was
reopened after a summer suspension in Imola.
</P>
<P>
He was summoned by prosecutor Maurizio Passarini to give
further testimony about the possible cracking of the steering
column in Senna's Williams-Renault car.
</P>
<P>
Alboreto's testimony gave strength to the prosecution's case in
the trial of six top Formul One officials charged with
manslaughter in the death of Senna.
</P>
<P>
The trial, which began in February, is seen as a potential
threat to auto racing in Italy.
</P>
<P>
FIA, the world governing body of the sport, suggested that F-1
teams may be afraid to race on Italian circuits if there are
convictions.
</P>
<P>
The six defendants could face up to five years in prison if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
The defendants include Frank Williams and Patrick Head, chief
and technical director of the Williams team.
</P>
<P>
Former Williams team designer Adrian Newey is also standing
trial, along with race organizer Federico Bendinelli, circuit
manager Giorgio Poggi and race director Roland Bruynseraede.
</P>
</TEXT>
