<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Investment Budget Cuts Needed for Thai Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has called
for further cuts in the investment budgets of both government
agencies and state enterprises this year and next year.
</P>
<P>
A further reduction in budgets for the two years will have to
be made to improve the government's fiscal position as required by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), according to a government
house spokesman on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of an agreement with the IMF, which brokered a
17.2 billion US dollar rescue fund, the Thai government must
produce a consolidated public sector surplus equivalent to one
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) in the 1998 fiscal
year beginning on October 1 this year. And the fiscal deficit
this year must not exceed 1.6 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Deputy prime minister Virabongsa Ramangura, who is in charge of
financial matters, is proposing that all tied-over budgets from
fiscal 1997 be reviewed, according to government spokesman
Varathep Rattanakorn.
</P>
<P>
If all tied-over budgets are cut, the government would come
closer to balancing the books, Virabongsa was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But if there will still be a shortfall, more measures will be
needed to increase government revenues, such as a higher excise
tax on oil and luxury goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
