<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Create Million New Jobs, Bank Predicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy will
experience growth and see the creation of one million new jobs by
the end of the century as momentum for new development builds, the
Toronto Dominion Bank predicted today.
</P>
<P>
"The Canadian economy is finally firing on all cylinders -- and
that spells great news for jobs," said Ruth Getter, the bank's
senior vice president and chief economist.
</P>
<P>
"Almost 400,000 new jobs will be created this year, and we
expect another 300,000 jobs to be added in both 1998 and 1999,"
Getter said in the bank's latest quarterly economic forecast.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted that Canada, which is outperforming the
other G-7 nations this year, will widen its lead even further in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Canada's real gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to grow
3.7 percent this year, 3.5 percent next and 2.8 percent in 1999,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The country's unemployment will edge down to 9.2 percent this
year, and 8.8 and 8.6 percent in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
"Although the Bank of Canada may raise interest rates as the
economic expansion picks up steam, interest rates will still
remain at very low levels," Getter said.
</P>
<P>
Canada now has "an environment that can support a fairly long
period of sustained economic growth," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
