<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Ease Rules on Foreign Exchange Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank
has approved in principle the exclusion of foreign exchange
subsidiaries and affiliates of banks from the 25,000-U.S.-dollar
cap on over-the-counter dollar sales.
</P>
<P>
Manila Bulletin reported today that the monetary authorities
have considered amending the ruling on foreign exchange
corporations of banks in response to a request from the Foreign
Exchange Association of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is excluding foreign exchange affiliates and
subsidiaries from the limitation on condition they do not sell
dollars to non-residents as well as financial institutions which
are with agent banks, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Over-the-counter dollar sales are transactions that require no
documentation, or prior approval from the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The monetary authorities ordered last week that foreign
exchange subsidiaries and affiliates of banks should be governed
under the same rules and regulations applicable to the banks.
</P>
<P>
However, currency dealers sought a "distinction" between rules
and regulations covering foreign exchange subsidiaries of banks
and those for the banks themselves.
</P>
<P>
The 25,000-U.S.-dollar cap had virtually paralyzed the
transaction of foreign exchange corporations, because it cramped
the ability of banks to service the dollar requirements of these
corporations.
</P>
<P>
"The limitation virtually renders foreign exchange corporations
of banks useless," a treasury official of a universal bank said.
</P>
<P>
Banks normally course their dollar requirements through foreign
exchange corporations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Builds New Satellite City In Northern Suburbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A new city for 250,000 to
300,000 people is under construction in the northern suburbs of
the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Wangjing New City will cover 860 hectares in a large complex of
apartment buildings, finance and trade zones, governmental
buildings, and cultural and service facilities.
</P>
<P>
The modern city will have plenty of green, forest parks, and
sports facilities and a 300-meter-tall building, the tallest in
the Chinese capital. The New City will be connected to downtown
Beijing by elevated trains and subways, according to the Beijing
Urban Construction and Development Corp., the City's developer.
</P>
<P>
Projects now underway include apartment buildings, major roads,
a telephone exchange with 150,000 lines, and a sewage plant.
</P>
<P>
Wangjing is believed to be one of the largest residential
communities in Asia and one of ten satellite cities around
Beijing, a metropolis of 12 million people, according to a general
development outline of the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
