<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shijiazhuang Becomes Market Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Shijiazhuang, capital of
north China's Hebei Province, has set its sights on becoming a
market city and a regional commercial center.
</P>
<P>
The city has made a great effort to build markets and
establish trade companies in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Shijiazhuang is currently home to 130,000 commercial outlets,
including 28 major retail department stores with a floor space of
at least 5,000 sq.m. each.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has either completed or is constructing
eight shopping streets.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua Trade Center and Nansantiao Marketplace with
respective 1996 sales of six billion yuan and 4.1 billion yuan,
rank among the nation's top 10 markets.
</P>
<P>
The city has also opened 10 markets handling capital goods,
including building materials, rolled steel and timber.
</P>
<P>
New markets and department stores constructed in recent years
feature modern architectural design and have advanced equipment,
including air-conditioning systems, elevators and escalators,
computerized alarm systems and modern fire-fighting devices.
</P>
<P>
The city has also restructured numerous local commercial
enterprises, with 28 firms restructured into joint-stock companies
or limited-liability companies and an additional 25 into
cooperative joint stock ventures.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 percent of local small and to medium-sized commercial
firms have adopted various forms of the cooperative joint-stock
system.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a number of enterprise groups and chain stores
have been established in the city's commercial sector.
</P>
<P>
Reform has promoted commercial prosperity and development in
Shijiazhuang. The city's 1996 retail sales soared to 20.2 billion
yuan, up 22 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
