<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Strengthens Quarantine Measures Against Pig Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian authorities
have strengthened quarantine measures in towns near the country's
common border with Costa Rica, in an effort to prevent possible
entry of pig fever from neighboring Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Supervision and vaccination measures have also been
strengthened in the border zone, after cases of the deadly pig
disease were detected in Costa Rica, vice minister of Agriculture
and Livestock Development (MIDA), Manuel Miranda, was quoted as
saying by the local press today.
</P>
<P>
Miranda said that in view of imminent propagation of the pig
disease, his Ministry has taken measures of monitor and control
involving MIDA technicians in the border towns.
</P>
<P>
"The sanitary campaign implemented by Panama will be reinforced
by setting up veterinarian posts along the border zone," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Another measure involved the suspension of free pig and cattle
dealing between raisers of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
