<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guerrillas Attack Police Plane in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A fleet of planes
escorting a mission of British diplomats was attacked by Colombian
guerrillas today in the southern province of Huila, with a pilot
slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said the shooting took place at 10:30
a.m. in a mountainous area in Vegalarga in the border between the
Huila and Caqueta provinces.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred after Tony Lloyd, Britain's minister of
state for Latin America and Africa in the Foreign Office, and
other British officials had made an inspection tour by air of the
two provinces. Colombian officials said the British diplomats was
accompanied by Colombian National Police chief Jose Serrano.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said an escort aircraft was hit by six shots
fired from the ground and its pilot suffered slight injuries.
</P>
<P>
He said the VIP aircraft was not damaged. Serrano and the
British diplomats had already landed when the guerrillas opened
fire at the escort aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Two escort helicopters returned fire following the attack, and
Lloyd arrived in Colombia Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Not All Venues to Maintain Perimeter in '98 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- France will decide on a "case
by case" basis whether to erect or maintain perimeter fencing at
its 10 World Cup stadiums next year.
</P>
<P>
During a tour of Lens' Blooaert ground, one of the venues for
the 1998 finals, French interior minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement
said security should be managed case by case because no venue
ressembled another.
</P>
<P>
Chevevement added that maintaining security was a question
above all and he would shortly be contacting the World Cup
Organising Committee (CFO), jointly headed by Michel Platini and
FIFA, soccer's world governing body.
</P>
<P>
Former France captain Platini said at the weekend he hoped
France's new government, elected in June, would choose to remove
perimeter fencing for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
FIFA also wants a tournament without fences but the former
government had decided they should stay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Improving Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Tourism authorities in Hainan,
China's island province in the south, are controlling the number
of new hotels for tourists and travel agencies in an effort to
improve their competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say the Provincial Tourism Administration will
suspend issuing licenses to new travel agencies or hotels in urban
areas and will not approve any ethnic song and dance programs over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
However, the suspension will not apply to hotels and villas to
be built with foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The move comes when Hainan's tourism industry is caught in a
downward spiral in service quality and profits, despite a growing
number of tourists.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the province had some five million tourists.
</P>
<P>
However, the large number of hotels has kept the hotel
occupancy rate low and competition too intense among the many
travel agencies, bringing the profit margin down to an
unreasonably low level. Low-quality service is beginning to hurt
the province's image.
</P>
<P>
The province has closed 164 travel agencies that don't have
licenses and suspended business at another 35 that failed to pass
the annual provincial tourism administration inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
