<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Mining giant Rio Tinto was yesterday awarded the right to
seek injunctions and millions of dollars in damages against
coal-mining union officials when Australia's Industrial Relations
Commission found pickets in huge coal-producing Hunter Valley
unlawful under the Workplace Relations Act. The coal-mining union
responded with a threatened shutdown of Australia's biggest export
industry.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- South Pacific region could lose its battle to stop thousands
of tons of nuclear waste being stored in the Marshall Islands of
Micronesia under an agreement reached between the Marshall Islands
government and B &AMP; W Nuclear Environmental Service, an American
company, in May.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Prime Minister John Howard flies out of Canberra
this morning for the South Pacific Forum in the Cook Islands amid
claims from Greenpeace that Australia is using its 324 million
U.S. dollar South Pacific aid budget to blackmail regional
countries over efforts to reduce global warming.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign investors are set to be limited to just 25 percent
of the allocated shares in Australia's telecommunications giant
Telstra float, after stronger-than-expected interest from
prospective Australian buyers. About 8.6 billion U.S. dollars'
worth of shares, or one third of the company's total, will be
privatized as part of the country's privatization program.
</P>
