<DOCNO> XIE19970917.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Erupts Again near Afghan Northern City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting erupted
again near Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of Afghan capital
of Kabul, between the Islamic Taliban militia and their rival
northern alliance, Afghan sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The fighting was back in areas about 30 km east of the
Afghanistan's second largest city, stronghold of the anti-Taliban
alliance led mainly by Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik and former
military chief Ahmad Masood, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Latest Taliban advances were be the second time the militia
moved close to the city within a week, after being beaten back
last Friday from a point only 18 kilometers from Mazar-e-Sharif,
the only major Afghan city not in Taliban's hands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.N. agencies are being compelled to temporarily
withdraw aid workers from Mazar-e-Sharif because their offices
have been so severely looted that they can no longer function.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no way at the moment that we can continue
to provide vital help to the poorest and most vulnerable people in
Mazar, so we are withdrawing our staff until security conditions
improve sufficiently to restart relief programs," said Bronek
Szynalski, regional director of the World Food Program (WFP) and
acting U.N. coordinator for Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The WFP compound has been stripped bare," Bronek said in a
statement issued here Tuesday, adding the WFP has lost 735 tons of
food and large quantities of drugs and other medical supplies .
</P>
<P>
Other U.N. offices have also been comprehensively looted of
thousands of dollars worth of computers, walkie-talkie radios,
vehicles and so on, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the second time this year that our Mazar premises have
been robbed in this way, in clear violation of U.N. immunities,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
These events keep hindering their efforts to help hundreds of
thousands of people who depend on international assistance in
Afghanistan, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
