<HEADLINE> US Doctors Over-Prescribe Antibiotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in the United
States wrote 12 million almost-useless antibiotic prescriptions
for colds, bronchitis and other respiratory infections in one
year, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, doctors prescribed antibiotics to two-thirds of
bronchitis sufferers, half of common-cold sufferers and patients
with other upper respiratory infections, according to the latest
issue of the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
That amounted to 12 million prescriptions, or one in every five
antibiotic prescriptions written for adults that year, researchers
said.
</P>
<P>
The 1992 figures were the latest available for the study, but
the 1995 numbers have since become available and are similar.
</P>
<P>
The indiscriminate use of antibiotics has contributed to the
emergence of drug-resistant bacteria, a growing problem in the
U.S., said the journal.
</P>
<P>
Studies have suggested many doctors may yield to pressure from
patients, or what they perceive to be the patients' expectations,
to prescribe a drug, even if it is unlikely to help.
</P>
<P>
"Every time we use an antibiotic, we run the risk of promoting
antibiotic resistance, or drug resistance, by bacteria," said the
lead author, Dr. Ralph Gonzales of the University of Colorado
Health Sciences Center in Denver.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial of the journal, Dr. Benjamin Schwartz of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention called for "an
immediate and aggressive response" to combat inappropriate
prescribing of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
"We encourage all physicians to examine their own practices and
identify where they can decrease unnecessary antimicrobial use,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
