<HEADLINE> US Calls Jews Moving Into Arab Property "Negative" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
said the moving of two Jewish families into formerly Arab-owned
property in East Jerusalem would have "a negative impact" on the
already moribund peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We think it would have a negative impact on the overall
process," State Department spokesman James Foley said at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
The two Jewish families moved Sunday into the houses, which
they said had been bought for them by Jewish-American tycoon
Irving Moskowitz. But Palestinians said the houses were never
sold.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also said at the Shannon
airport, Ireland, on the way back from her maiden trip to the
Middle East, that that was "not a helpful act."
</P>
<P>
Foley told reporters Albright spoke clearly about the need to
"avoid unilateral actions or actions which tended to undermine
confidence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
