<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Attacks US Visa Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is
stepping up its attack on a new U.S. immigration law that would
impose severe curbs on millions of Canadians who travel south to
the U.S., said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Canadian officials are going public with their fight over the
law after several failed bids to get the U.S. Congress to amend
it, according to the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The law, passed last year, would force all foreigners to fill
out visa forms upon entering the United States starting next
September.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Canadians who travel to the U.S. would have to fill
out the forms, which would formalize the inquiries immigration
officers often currently make orally of those crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
By 1999, Canadians crossing the border would also be required
to obtain an identification card encoded with key passport and
handprint information.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Ambassador to the U.S. Raymond Chretien complained in
a recent letter to key members of the Congress that the law would
cause traffic chaos at already-congested points along the border
and disrupt bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
"Implementation of this act as it presently stands would have a
severe adverse impact on cross-border traffic at U.S. land ports
of entry," Chretien wrote.
</P>
<P>
"Citizens of our two countries have long enjoyed free and easy
access across our borders.... Clearly (the law) takes us in the
wrong direction," he said.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown is also at odds with public statements by
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien and U.S. President Bill
Clinton on the increasingly open border, one Canadian official
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. law will be phased in starting in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
